    "{\"#\":384,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-15T02:19:37.470678Z\",\"event\":{\"SavedViewUpdate:2\":{\"id\":7,\"values\":[{\"filter\":{\"all\":[{\"not\":{\"reqType\":3}},{\"not\":{\"reqType\":3}},{\"not\":{\"hash\":{\"r\":14}}},{\"not\":{\"hash\":{\"r\":16}}},{\"not\":{\"hash\":{\"r\":17}}}]}}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":385,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-15T02:23:57.018508Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":72,\"reqTypeId\":3,\"values\":[{\"customText\":{\"1\":[{\"lit\":\"Allow specification of rules to allow ShipReq to dynamically and automatically modify/override tag values for reqs based on the tags of implied children.\"}]}},{\"title\":[{\"lit\":\"Derivative tags\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":386,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-15T02:27:43.544225Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":73,\"reqTypeId\":6,\"values\":[{\"customText\":{\"6\":[{\"lit\":\"me\"}]}},{\"impTgts\":[{\"gr\":72}]},{\"tags\":[13]},{\"title\":[{\"lit\":\"After implementing reqs, I don't want to manually have to go through all the parent reqs and change their status to \"},{\"mono\":\"implemented\"},{\"lit\":\". I want to just change the status of my leaf-node reqs as I implement them and have all the parents' statuses update automatically.\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":387,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-15T02:29:55.576880Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":74,\"reqTypeId\":6,\"values\":[{\"customText\":{\"6\":[{\"lit\":\"me\"}]}},{\"impTgts\":[{\"gr\":32}]},{\"tags\":[13]},{\"title\":[{\"lit\":\"I don't want to have to come back to ShipReq every time I implement a req. I want to just commit my code with something like \"},{\"mono\":\"Implements FR-34\"},{\"lit\":\" and have it automatically modify the status in ShipReq.\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":388,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-30T00:13:00.506395Z\",\"event\":{\"CustomReqTypeCreate:2\":{\"id\":10,\"values\":[{\"desc\":null},{\"imp\":false},{\"mnemonic\":\"IV\"},{\"name\":\"Interview\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":389,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-30T00:14:58.200940Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":75,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[{\"title\":[{\"lit\":\"Organisation & Completeness Evaluation\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":390,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-30T00:16:28.000702Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":75},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Organisation\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Now that the basic system is up and running, something's are gonna be hard as the usage increases. Currently I can write and store and share usecases, as the number of usecases grow looking at them all as a flat list isn't going to make sense. I'm need to organise them somehow, 1) so that the list isn't overwhelming, and 2) because I need that organisation for other purposes.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The first type of organisation or grouping that comes to mind (and need) is versioning. I need to keep track of which usecases are in which version so that when I'm working on that I can narrow my focus to relevant usecases and ignore the rest. Groupings should be arbitrary, I don't want to be restricted to versions. JIRA has issue type, components and more; Github uses labels/tags like AwaitingInfo, Enhancement, Defect, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I was thinking, the real-world system, and real-world model... Ucs are descriptions of interaction. A version has nothing to do with it. It's separate. Versions are their own entities, part of a project schedule. Users should be able to change which Ucs are in which version without opening a UC, or affecting the content of a UC. In real-life the contents of a version can change very quickly and spontaneously.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What's similar? … Affected components (isn't that the actors?). I'm not sure if actors will suffice for this. But I know that grouping Ucs by it would be very important. Different teams of people can be responsible for different components and they will often want to only see Ucs for their own component(s). In real life it's: UC (interaction desc) → multiple components → people. People have their own org strategies (esp. team), components have their own relationships (eg. A and B are part of X).\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Users might just need to group Ucs together. Maybe Ucs 1-8 all relation to a particular function (eg. stock trading)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Priorities are a big one! Similar to versions, fickle and ephemeral, change often, arbitrary strategies/definitions/schemes/approaches. They need an ordering between them (ie. High > med > low). Versions will need that too actually (ie. 1.9 < 1.9.1 < 1.10 < 1.11)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Any organisational units should be applicable to share UC selection. (Eg. Have a share that shows high-pri for 1.x)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Interestingly versions have their own attributes: release date; status/state = pending, in progress, released, in testing; more?) I might want to create a share that shows Ucs for all unreleased versions.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also some org units might have different cardinality restrictions. 1 version might be required, 1+ components might be required. If a UC is missing a version of component a user would probably want to be able to see, identify and correct that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Complication: Use cases are not always implemented in full. It's normal for 90% of a UC to be in scope for version A, and then the remaining 10% to go in version C. Usually this is because parts of the UC depend on another UC that isn't in the same scope. Function requirements are probably atomic enough to be assigned to a single version without issue.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Completeness Evaluation\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Secondly, I also need to know which usecases are complete and which still need work. Usecases will often be a work in progress, filled with TODOs and TBDs, empty fields. I need a way to access the state of (in)completeness across my all usecases without having to click and manually read each one.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"What kind of precision is required?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"How critical to the business value is this feature?\"}]]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"SEPARATELY: Browse thru study notes, collect good product/global-scope questions, prepare form, answer the next day.\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":391,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-30T00:18:35.935725Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":75},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":392,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-30T00:18:51.770271Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":75},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":6},{\"gr\":7}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":393,\"createdAt\":\"2020-06-30T00:19:15.178750Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":75},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Organisation\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Now that the basic system is up and running, something's are gonna be hard as the usage increases. Currently I can write and store and share usecases, as the number of usecases grow looking at them all as a flat list isn't going to make sense. I'm need to organise them somehow, 1) so that the list isn't overwhelming, and 2) because I need that organisation for other purposes.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The first type of organisation or grouping that comes to mind (and need) is versioning. I need to keep track of which usecases are in which version so that when I'm working on that I can narrow my focus to relevant usecases and ignore the rest. Groupings should be arbitrary, I don't want to be restricted to versions. JIRA has issue type, components and more; Github uses labels/tags like AwaitingInfo, Enhancement, Defect, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I was thinking, the real-world system, and real-world model... Ucs are descriptions of interaction. A version has nothing to do with it. It's separate. Versions are their own entities, part of a project schedule. Users should be able to change which Ucs are in which version without opening a UC, or affecting the content of a UC. In real-life the contents of a version can change very quickly and spontaneously.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What's similar? … Affected components (isn't that the actors?). I'm not sure if actors will suffice for this. But I know that grouping Ucs by it would be very important. Different teams of people can be responsible for different components and they will often want to only see Ucs for their own component(s). In real life it's: UC (interaction desc) → multiple components → people. People have their own org strategies (esp. team), components have their own relationships (eg. A and B are part of X).\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Users might just need to group Ucs together. Maybe Ucs 1-8 all relation to a particular function (eg. stock trading)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Priorities are a big one! Similar to versions, fickle and ephemeral, change often, arbitrary strategies/definitions/schemes/approaches. They need an ordering between them (ie. High > med > low). Versions will need that too actually (ie. 1.9 < 1.9.1 < 1.10 < 1.11)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Any organisational units should be applicable to share UC selection. (Eg. Have a share that shows high-pri for 1.x)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Interestingly versions have their own attributes: release date; status/state = pending, in progress, released, in testing; more?) I might want to create a share that shows Ucs for all unreleased versions.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also some org units might have different cardinality restrictions. 1 version might be required, 1+ components might be required. If a UC is missing a version of component a user would probably want to be able to see, identify and correct that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Complication: Use cases are not always implemented in full. It's normal for 90% of a UC to be in scope for version A, and then the remaining 10% to go in version C. Usually this is because parts of the UC depend on another UC that isn't in the same scope. Function requirements are probably atomic enough to be assigned to a single version without issue.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Completeness Evaluation \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"(= incompletions = issues)\"}]}]},{\"lit\":\"Secondly, I also need to know which usecases are complete and which still need work. Usecases will often be a work in progress, filled with TODOs and TBDs, empty fields. I need a way to access the state of (in)completeness across my all usecases without having to click and manually read each one.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"What kind of precision is required?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"How critical to the business value is this feature?\"}]]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"SEPARATELY: Browse thru study notes, collect good product/global-scope questions, prepare form, answer the next day.\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":394,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T06:24:50.452480Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":76,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":395,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T06:25:24.033126Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":76,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Bulk\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":396,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T06:29:04.761825Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":76},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"[Organisation]\"}]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[17/12/2013: Continuing on...]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I was reading about Feature Trees. It's a very simple method of organisation and mind-mapping. You start with the project/app in the center, draw a line out of it to a box which is a feature. Now along that line draw protruding lines (like brnahces on a tree) which are the use cases required to implement, or just pertaining to, the feature. Simple and effective. (Additionally, the book recommends writing functional requirements underneath the UCs but that's a bit verbose. Although a dynamic and interactive diagram might be perfect! Scroll around, zoom into an area, see the functional requirements appear. Cool.)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Anyway, I thought about this a little more and Features are just collections of smaller capabilities. They fit the same model described above. They have an n:n mapping with UCs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Acutally, they can have their own priority which would probably be either 1) a multiplier to their children UCs' priorities, or 2) a parent priority that would take precedence over the children's priorities. Interesting. Once these were in-place some nice graphs might be doable, I'm imagining a table or grid, versions at the top, features on the left, and then colours boxes in the middle overlapping versions and... wait that doesn't make sense, there's no overlap. It would just be like the Major Features & Release Plan in V&S docs. Well maybe priority could be introduced. For some reason I imagine different coloured semi-transparent bars overlapping being extremely useful as a visualisation tool. Coming from my subconcious or gut, I'll need to think about that later. One thing is for sure though, automatic or easily generatable diagrams will get lots of points with potential users I think. They appeal. Good diagrams are orders of magnitude more efficient at conveying information that text. They're usually harder to manually draw and maintain than text. Even if I invent my own diagrams, they should provide a lot of business value.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Where was I? Organisation. Yes! Well Features are another organisational device, they may have their own (arbitrary) attributes, how their attributes affect UC attributes (if at all) will likely be arbitrary.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When the system gets versions, I would to see a list of versions and as first-class list items. What I mean is, unlike Github and JIRA where you see a list of issues and then apply filters, I want to just see a list of versions, maybe with a little footnote for each one like “23 UCs” or something. Similar to how at the moment you log in, you see projects, click a project you see UCs. I want to see Versions, click, see UCs. I would like the same thing with Features. It would probably be good to be able to do it for all units of organisation. The ability to do it with multiple levels (eg. ver → component) or maybe matrix/filter style would be the trick!\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Two of the most important project goals are simplicity and ease. Therefore the following must be considered:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Sensible and intuitive defaults.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Effort to use.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Effort to learn, understand how to modify.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Separate and minimise intertwined functions & responsibilities.\"}]]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[Just went and wrote Requirements/project-attributes.ods]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Ok, later I should run all my requirements through my project-attributes doc and customise the design.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also how will these organisational units affect publish-views? Should they be present? Toggleable?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will they affect UCE also? Lots of people like Priority in its own field.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will these affect UC revision?\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"[Read All UCs & Generate PDF]\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I didn't put too much thought into these two functions when I built them into the prototype.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I originally wanted the features for the following reasons:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"So I could see/confirm the layout/markup before sharing/printing.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"So I could read through and review all my UCs.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"I see the two random buttons in the prototype as a problem now because:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"You can't filter the UCs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"You can't add a title & preface.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Actually I think I need the same thing as a share, except with the password. Probably overkill saving the “view” or whatnot. Maybe I could be [main] → [filter] ↔ [view] → [pdf]. Something like that would then allow anon users to filter shares they look at and generate a pdf too. Might be useful. Guessing...\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"[Completeness Evaluation]\"}]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[04/12/2013: I also need to know which usecases are complete and which still need work. Usecases will often be a work in progress, filled with TODOs and TBDs, empty fields. I need a way to access the state of (in)completeness across my all usecases without having to click and manually read each one. ]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When I'm revising UCs I want the following:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"To know which UCs have bad tags, and how many: [DELETED] refs, invalid step refs, invalid UC refs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"To know which UCs have these, and how many: TODOs, TBDs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"To know which UCs have empty (mandatory) fields, and how many.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"To be able to see all of the above in context without having to open each UC.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Total number of above.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Ability to filter UC scope.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"The pros usually add additional info to TODOs and TBDs such as who is responsible for the next step, when they expect to know, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It might be an idea to auto-populate new UCs with TODOs in each field and use that instead of considering empty fields a problem. Or maybe have the ability to switch empty fields on/off.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"[Field Management]\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Users will likely need to configure their own UC fields. This includes:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Removing fields.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Reordering fields.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Adding new fields.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Changing existing fields.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"This field set should apply to all UCs in the project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"To be super-detailed, this \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"could\"}]},{\"lit\":\" be applied on a UC-by-UC basis, even more extreme would be UCs belonging to a given component get special fieldset modifications. But I think that's way too detailed.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"This affects \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":6}},{\"lit\":\". If a user decides they want an extra field for a subset of UCs, then unless functionality for that is provided, they will just add to all and either leave blank on irrelevant UCs, or fill with N/A. If they want to leave it empty then it may be considered a TODO within \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":6}},{\"lit\":\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When the user is configuring their fieldset, it should show them how many UCs are currently using a field and even show them the values. I might think “oh I don't use XXX, I'll just delete it”, where as I might be using it quite effectively in some UCs. Also do we hard delete their data? Maybe we should just soft delete and be able to swtich it on again later.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":397,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T06:29:41.335404Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":75},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":7}},{\"lit\":\" Organisation\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Now that the basic system is up and running, something's are gonna be hard as the usage increases. Currently I can write and store and share usecases, as the number of usecases grow looking at them all as a flat list isn't going to make sense. I'm need to organise them somehow, 1) so that the list isn't overwhelming, and 2) because I need that organisation for other purposes.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The first type of organisation or grouping that comes to mind (and need) is versioning. I need to keep track of which usecases are in which version so that when I'm working on that I can narrow my focus to relevant usecases and ignore the rest. Groupings should be arbitrary, I don't want to be restricted to versions. JIRA has issue type, components and more; Github uses labels/tags like AwaitingInfo, Enhancement, Defect, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I was thinking, the real-world system, and real-world model... Ucs are descriptions of interaction. A version has nothing to do with it. It's separate. Versions are their own entities, part of a project schedule. Users should be able to change which Ucs are in which version without opening a UC, or affecting the content of a UC. In real-life the contents of a version can change very quickly and spontaneously.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What's similar? … Affected components (isn't that the actors?). I'm not sure if actors will suffice for this. But I know that grouping Ucs by it would be very important. Different teams of people can be responsible for different components and they will often want to only see Ucs for their own component(s). In real life it's: UC (interaction desc) → multiple components → people. People have their own org strategies (esp. team), components have their own relationships (eg. A and B are part of X).\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Users might just need to group Ucs together. Maybe Ucs 1-8 all relation to a particular function (eg. stock trading)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Priorities are a big one! Similar to versions, fickle and ephemeral, change often, arbitrary strategies/definitions/schemes/approaches. They need an ordering between them (ie. High > med > low). Versions will need that too actually (ie. 1.9 < 1.9.1 < 1.10 < 1.11)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Any organisational units should be applicable to share UC selection. (Eg. Have a share that shows high-pri for 1.x)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Interestingly versions have their own attributes: release date; status/state = pending, in progress, released, in testing; more?) I might want to create a share that shows Ucs for all unreleased versions.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also some org units might have different cardinality restrictions. 1 version might be required, 1+ components might be required. If a UC is missing a version of component a user would probably want to be able to see, identify and correct that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Complication: Use cases are not always implemented in full. It's normal for 90% of a UC to be in scope for version A, and then the remaining 10% to go in version C. Usually this is because parts of the UC depend on another UC that isn't in the same scope. Function requirements are probably atomic enough to be assigned to a single version without issue.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":6}},{\"lit\":\" Completeness Evaluation \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"(= incompletions = issues)\"}]}]},{\"lit\":\"Secondly, I also need to know which usecases are complete and which still need work. Usecases will often be a work in progress, filled with TODOs and TBDs, empty fields. I need a way to access the state of (in)completeness across my all usecases without having to click and manually read each one.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"What kind of precision is required?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"How critical to the business value is this feature?\"}]]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"SEPARATELY: Browse thru study notes, collect good product/global-scope questions, prepare form, answer the next day.\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":398,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T06:30:23.591286Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":76},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":7}},{\"lit\":\" Organisation\"}]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[17/12/2013: Continuing on...]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I was reading about Feature Trees. It's a very simple method of organisation and mind-mapping. You start with the project/app in the center, draw a line out of it to a box which is a feature. Now along that line draw protruding lines (like brnahces on a tree) which are the use cases required to implement, or just pertaining to, the feature. Simple and effective. (Additionally, the book recommends writing functional requirements underneath the UCs but that's a bit verbose. Although a dynamic and interactive diagram might be perfect! Scroll around, zoom into an area, see the functional requirements appear. Cool.)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Anyway, I thought about this a little more and Features are just collections of smaller capabilities. They fit the same model described above. They have an n:n mapping with UCs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Acutally, they can have their own priority which would probably be either 1) a multiplier to their children UCs' priorities, or 2) a parent priority that would take precedence over the children's priorities. Interesting. Once these were in-place some nice graphs might be doable, I'm imagining a table or grid, versions at the top, features on the left, and then colours boxes in the middle overlapping versions and... wait that doesn't make sense, there's no overlap. It would just be like the Major Features & Release Plan in V&S docs. Well maybe priority could be introduced. For some reason I imagine different coloured semi-transparent bars overlapping being extremely useful as a visualisation tool. Coming from my subconcious or gut, I'll need to think about that later. One thing is for sure though, automatic or easily generatable diagrams will get lots of points with potential users I think. They appeal. Good diagrams are orders of magnitude more efficient at conveying information that text. They're usually harder to manually draw and maintain than text. Even if I invent my own diagrams, they should provide a lot of business value.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Where was I? Organisation. Yes! Well Features are another organisational device, they may have their own (arbitrary) attributes, how their attributes affect UC attributes (if at all) will likely be arbitrary.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When the system gets versions, I would to see a list of versions and as first-class list items. What I mean is, unlike Github and JIRA where you see a list of issues and then apply filters, I want to just see a list of versions, maybe with a little footnote for each one like “23 UCs” or something. Similar to how at the moment you log in, you see projects, click a project you see UCs. I want to see Versions, click, see UCs. I would like the same thing with Features. It would probably be good to be able to do it for all units of organisation. The ability to do it with multiple levels (eg. ver → component) or maybe matrix/filter style would be the trick!\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Two of the most important project goals are simplicity and ease. Therefore the following must be considered:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Sensible and intuitive defaults.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Effort to use.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Effort to learn, understand how to modify.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Separate and minimise intertwined functions & responsibilities.\"}]]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[Just went and wrote Requirements/project-attributes.ods]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Ok, later I should run all my requirements through my project-attributes doc and customise the design.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also how will these organisational units affect publish-views? Should they be present? Toggleable?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will they affect UCE also? Lots of people like Priority in its own field.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will these affect UC revision?\"},{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":3}},{\"lit\":\" Read All UCs & Generate PDF\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I didn't put too much thought into these two functions when I built them into the prototype.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I originally wanted the features for the following reasons:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"So I could see/confirm the layout/markup before sharing/printing.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"So I could read through and review all my UCs.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"I see the two random buttons in the prototype as a problem now because:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"You can't filter the UCs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"You can't add a title & preface.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Actually I think I need the same thing as a share, except with the password. Probably overkill saving the “view” or whatnot. Maybe I could be [main] → [filter] ↔ [view] → [pdf]. Something like that would then allow anon users to filter shares they look at and generate a pdf too. Might be useful. Guessing...\"},{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":6}},{\"lit\":\" Completeness Evaluation\"}]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[04/12/2013: I also need to know which usecases are complete and which still need work. Usecases will often be a work in progress, filled with TODOs and TBDs, empty fields. I need a way to access the state of (in)completeness across my all usecases without having to click and manually read each one. ]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When I'm revising UCs I want the following:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"To know which UCs have bad tags, and how many: [DELETED] refs, invalid step refs, invalid UC refs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"To know which UCs have these, and how many: TODOs, TBDs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"To know which UCs have empty (mandatory) fields, and how many.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"To be able to see all of the above in context without having to open each UC.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Total number of above.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Ability to filter UC scope.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"The pros usually add additional info to TODOs and TBDs such as who is responsible for the next step, when they expect to know, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It might be an idea to auto-populate new UCs with TODOs in each field and use that instead of considering empty fields a problem. Or maybe have the ability to switch empty fields on/off.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":5}},{\"lit\":\" Field Management\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Users will likely need to configure their own UC fields. This includes:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Removing fields.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Reordering fields.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Adding new fields.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Changing existing fields.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"This field set should apply to all UCs in the project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"To be super-detailed, this \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"could\"}]},{\"lit\":\" be applied on a UC-by-UC basis, even more extreme would be UCs belonging to a given component get special fieldset modifications. But I think that's way too detailed.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"This affects \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":6}},{\"lit\":\". If a user decides they want an extra field for a subset of UCs, then unless functionality for that is provided, they will just add to all and either leave blank on irrelevant UCs, or fill with N/A. If they want to leave it empty then it may be considered a TODO within \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":6}},{\"lit\":\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When the user is configuring their fieldset, it should show them how many UCs are currently using a field and even show them the values. I might think “oh I don't use XXX, I'll just delete it”, where as I might be using it quite effectively in some UCs. Also do we hard delete their data? Maybe we should just soft delete and be able to swtich it on again later.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":399,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T06:31:10.926019Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":76},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":400,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T07:15:27.447011Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":77,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":401,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T07:18:34.204577Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":77},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":7}},{\"lit\":\" Organisation\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"You said previously “ I need […] organisation for other purposes”. What purposes can you think of? \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"([Q is ambiguous])\"}]}]},{\"lit\":\"I can think of these purposes:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"BA filtering UC scope when reading/printing/reviewing UCs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"A share filtering UC scope when being accessed by Readers.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"PM/BA determining the scope of their versions.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"BA accessing the influence/scope/size of an organisational unit. Inverse of 1.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Eg. How big is 1.0, how much work does Team A have to work with, what's completed.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Who is interested in those purposes and how important is it to them?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"1. BA. Very important as project grows. 10 Ucs = slightly important, 50 UCs important. 100+ UCs critical.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. BA & Readers. Same importance as above.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. BA/PM. Somewhat important.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"4. As above.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Why do those purposes matter?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. Near impossible to work without being to filter shit out.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. BA needs to manage amount of information washing over Reader. Also Reader, might not be privy to some requirements.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. PM/BA needs to estimate effort for Ucs in a version and balance it against time & cost.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"4. BA: Confirm allocations match what they've got in their head.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"PM: estimate effort/workload and balance it against external factors.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What would happen if you couldn't use the product to organise you Ucs in the groups?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. I would be very pissed off. I would have to use the editor to view each one-by-one. Wrt printing I'd just have to print everything and cross out certain UC titles.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. I would have to manually select Ucs. Every time a UC came in-scope or went out-of-scope I'd have to manually update all shares. Annoying.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. ?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Actually I misread. If the product didn't have any org features in it then I'd have only 2 options.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. Use some external tool (Excel) to do the same thing. I'd have a row that matched the requirement Ids and then columns for the org stuff. That would be annoying because I would have to either omit titles from the external doc or copy titles into it and then they'd get out of sync.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. I'd abuse the titles of Ucs to add extra information. Things like [VERSION: 1.0]. Things would get ugly.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If versions are metadata instead of real UC content, why do some people want them to look like they are part of the UC?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"People are used to it. It's the way it's commonly done. Decades of precedent.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"The distinction between content and org metadata is fine and not commonly recognised.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"When sharing/reviewing a UC the Reader will often like to see associated org data.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Where else to put it?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What about groupings other than version, do they all have the same relationship to Ucs? [Vague: Make relationships explicit.]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What attributes do <grouping> have?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"See feature-organisation.ods.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If groupings were implemented without attributes, what problems would still exist, or arise?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Looking at the direct attributes, it wouldn't be a big deal. If everything had a single description attribute tht would probably be more than enough. If there were no attributes at all, I don't think it would matter too much.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"For relation-attributes however, see feature-organisation.ods.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will the consequences be if <each one> is missing from the app?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"In the UC publish view, how is <grouping> normally integrated?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Why do readers of the doc need to see it?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"See feature-organisation.ods.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What's the trade-off between time and value?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Something must be done to solve the scope problem. Everything else is nice to have.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The value should be sufficient to solve the scope problem with high value costing up to a month of time.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of this solution?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Have an unorganised project of approx 100 Ucs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Organise all 100 in into 5 versions in under 10 minutes.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Have a version with 40 Ucs in it, redistribute every 5th UC in a different version in under 5 minutes. (eg. 20% to ver A, 20% to ver B, etc.)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"???\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"[Completeness Evaluation]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How do you deal with this situation currently?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Two ways:\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. View all use cases and manually scan text for keywords like TODO, TBD. If using MS Word I normally highlight in red so they stand out.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. Keep a separate table of pending tasks.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will you deal with it until an implementation is provided?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"One of the two ways above. Because the UCE doesn't allow me to colour text, I might even deliberately input invalid refs so that I have something red so my eyes see it fast.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Who is this important to? Why?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The UC editor and reviewer.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It's important because the issues these TODO tags represent need to addressed and not forgotten. Because the BA/reviewer will read multiple revisions of a UC, they naturally start to skim making it very easy to overlook important gaps in the requirements.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do after determining completeness?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If complete, maybe share for review, print it out maybe. Alert someone.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering empty fields?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Fill them in or enter a TODO/TBD with additional info.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering placeholders?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Try to edit the fields and resolve the incompletions.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"People could be happy with certain fields being empty which would yield false positives. At least in their mind empty fields could be of less value than TODOs so they wouldn't want to wade through a sea of empty-field errors looking for those few TODOs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How often would it be used?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Very often. Tags would be added nearly every time the UCE is opened for new requirements.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"After requirements start to settle the incompletion-overview function would be used regularly until all were gone.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When would it be used?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"All the time until the end of a project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When you say you want to see all incompletions in context without having to open each UC...\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"- why is this important?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The not-wanting-to-open-UC part is obvious. Much effort.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The context part... well I was just thinking of diffs actually. Hmm, well the incompletions just need enough info to make sense without seeing the entire UC. Otherwise displaying them all in a nice list will lose its value if the user then has to open a UC to understand it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"- what would happen if you couldn't see them in context?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"User would have to open containing UC; no point having a nice summary.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"- what do you expect to see when you say context? How much context?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"You'd definitely want to see the UC name, and containing field name for all incompletions.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If TODOs, TBDs etc are able to include additional data, that data should be displayed.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If not the entire field would need to be displayed.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"For invalid step/UC refs some of the surrounding text would be useful. Ideally the containing sentence. If not, maybe just a number of words before the tag (important) and a number after (less important).\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What kind of incompletions are there?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Empty fields\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Deleted step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid UC refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"User-defined tags: TODO, TBD.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What causes them in real-life?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Bad refs – Mistakes. Deletion of ref target.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Empty – Don't know/care. Not enough time.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"TODO/TBD – Need to think, need to talk to someone, awaiting external event.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What is the typical lifecycle of such an incompletion?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It occurs, you see it, you ignore it, you resolve or delete it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Can you think of or do you remember any variations?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"No.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Some fields are mandatory? How often does the mandatory-ness change?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Well that's at the discresion of the req manager. It can definitely change over time as the project gets underway.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also if a use case is missing a version or priority that is often considered an incompletion.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"[Field Management]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"“Users will likely need to configure their own UC fields.”\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Why?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Use cases are not set in stone. Teams have their preferences. Somethings work better than others depending on the team and project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How often?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Usually only once per-project. Sometimes fields are modified after ending a few UCs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do if they can't?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Be very dissatisfied with the product. Some teams will refuse to use it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Usually at the beginning of a project when less than 10 UCs have been entered.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Who?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The BA.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a team has a nice setup and needs to redo it for each project they would be unhappy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When you say change existing fields, what kind of changes can you imagine specifically?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Renaming it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Changing its mandatory status.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Changing its position wrt other fields.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When deleting a field, what should happen to its content? [Dev question]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It should be gone from all views.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a field is deleted it has content, should anyone still be able to see it? If so, how?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Well just after deletion it might be nice to see it in the editor so that I can copy & paste bits of it around elsewhere. Otherwise, no.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a field was deleted by mistake, in error or just by bad judgement, what would the consequences be?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Valuable data could be lost. If there are only a few UCs it would be bad, if there were many it could be disasterous.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What are the time/cost/effort implications of said consequences?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Could be absoluetly massive!\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What would you do to remedy the situation?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Would have to either reenter the info from previous copies lying around and/or from BA's memory, likely having to reengage the client.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of a solution?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Find various UCs online and in books with different structures and ensure the system supports creating them with the same or at least very similar structure.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"[Read All UCs & Generate PDF]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When & why would you want to view/read multiple UCs at once?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. When editing and/or reviewing my UCs to ensure correctness at a larger scope, find problems.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. To print out a subset to give/show someone.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. When performing some other tasks that depends on them. (Design, dev, requirements diagrams)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When & why would you want to print UCs?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. To read and/or review offline.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. To give to someone else to read/review.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. For safe-keeping. Hard copies can be a form of redundancy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How often would you want to perform <answers above>?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. Very often when working on UCs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. Often when working with others.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. Depends on the task. Occasional~Often.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. Occasional. Offline is a nice break from the PC.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. Often when working with others.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. Not often.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How important is a solution to you? What are the consequences of not having a solution?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Quite important. Without the ability to view and print multiple UCs at once, UCs are trapped in the app. Without the ability to filter these, the ability to view and print multiple UCs at once becomes increasingly useless as the UC count grows.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":402,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T07:41:28.536222Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":77},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"req\":{\"gr\":7}},{\"lit\":\" Organisation\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"You said previously “ I need […] organisation for other purposes”. What purposes can you think of? \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"([Q is ambiguous])\"}]}]},{\"lit\":\"I can think of these purposes:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"1. BA filtering UC scope when reading/printing/reviewing UCs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"2. A share filtering UC scope when being accessed by Readers.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"3. PM/BA determining the scope of their versions.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"4. BA accessing the influence/scope/size of an organisational unit. Inverse of 1.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Eg. How big is 1.0, how much work does Team A have to work with, what's completed.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Who is interested in those purposes and how important is it to them?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"1. BA. Very important as project grows. 10 Ucs = slightly important, 50 UCs important. 100+ UCs critical.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"2. BA & Readers. Same importance as above.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"3. BA/PM. Somewhat important.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"4. As above.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why do those purposes matter?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"1. Near impossible to work without being to filter shit out.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"2. BA needs to manage amount of information washing over Reader. Also Reader, might not be privy to some requirements.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"3. PM/BA needs to estimate effort for Ucs in a version and balance it against time & cost.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"4. BA: Confirm allocations match what they've got in their head.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"PM: estimate effort/workload and balance it against external factors.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would happen if you couldn't use the product to organise you Ucs in the groups?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"1. I would be very pissed off. I would have to use the editor to view each one-by-one. Wrt printing I'd just have to print everything and cross out certain UC titles.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"2. I would have to manually select Ucs. Every time a UC came in-scope or went out-of-scope I'd have to manually update all shares. Annoying.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"3. ?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Actually I misread. If the product didn't have any org features in it then I'd have only 2 options.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"1. Use some external tool (Excel) to do the same thing. I'd have a row that matched the requirement Ids and then columns for the org stuff. That would be annoying because I would have to either omit titles from the external doc or copy titles into it and then they'd get out of sync.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"2. I'd abuse the titles of Ucs to add extra information. Things like [VERSION: 1.0]. Things would get ugly.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"If versions are metadata instead of real UC content, why do some people want them to look like they are part of the UC?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"People are used to it. It's the way it's commonly done. Decades of precedent.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"The distinction between content and org metadata is fine and not commonly recognised.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"When sharing/reviewing a UC the Reader will often like to see associated org data.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Where else to put it?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What about groupings other than version, do they all have the same relationship to Ucs? [Vague: Make relationships explicit.]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What attributes do <grouping> have?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"See feature-organisation.ods.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If groupings were implemented without attributes, what problems would still exist, or arise?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Looking at the direct attributes, it wouldn't be a big deal. If everything had a single description attribute tht would probably be more than enough. If there were no attributes at all, I don't think it would matter too much.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"For relation-attributes however, see feature-organisation.ods.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will the consequences be if <each one> is missing from the app?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"In the UC publish view, how is <grouping> normally integrated?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Why do readers of the doc need to see it?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"See feature-organisation.ods.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What's the trade-off between time and value?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Something must be done to solve the scope problem. Everything else is nice to have.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The value should be sufficient to solve the scope problem with high value costing up to a month of time.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of this solution?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Have an unorganised project of approx 100 Ucs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Organise all 100 in into 5 versions in under 10 minutes.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Have a version with 40 Ucs in it, redistribute every 5th UC in a different version in under 5 minutes. (eg. 20% to ver A, 20% to ver B, etc.)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"???\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"[Completeness Evaluation]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How do you deal with this situation currently?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Two ways:\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. View all use cases and manually scan text for keywords like TODO, TBD. If using MS Word I normally highlight in red so they stand out.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. Keep a separate table of pending tasks.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will you deal with it until an implementation is provided?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"One of the two ways above. Because the UCE doesn't allow me to colour text, I might even deliberately input invalid refs so that I have something red so my eyes see it fast.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Who is this important to? Why?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The UC editor and reviewer.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It's important because the issues these TODO tags represent need to addressed and not forgotten. Because the BA/reviewer will read multiple revisions of a UC, they naturally start to skim making it very easy to overlook important gaps in the requirements.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do after determining completeness?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If complete, maybe share for review, print it out maybe. Alert someone.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering empty fields?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Fill them in or enter a TODO/TBD with additional info.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering placeholders?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Try to edit the fields and resolve the incompletions.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"People could be happy with certain fields being empty which would yield false positives. At least in their mind empty fields could be of less value than TODOs so they wouldn't want to wade through a sea of empty-field errors looking for those few TODOs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How often would it be used?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Very often. Tags would be added nearly every time the UCE is opened for new requirements.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"After requirements start to settle the incompletion-overview function would be used regularly until all were gone.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When would it be used?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"All the time until the end of a project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When you say you want to see all incompletions in context without having to open each UC...\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"- why is this important?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The not-wanting-to-open-UC part is obvious. Much effort.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The context part... well I was just thinking of diffs actually. Hmm, well the incompletions just need enough info to make sense without seeing the entire UC. Otherwise displaying them all in a nice list will lose its value if the user then has to open a UC to understand it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"- what would happen if you couldn't see them in context?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"User would have to open containing UC; no point having a nice summary.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"- what do you expect to see when you say context? How much context?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"You'd definitely want to see the UC name, and containing field name for all incompletions.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If TODOs, TBDs etc are able to include additional data, that data should be displayed.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If not the entire field would need to be displayed.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"For invalid step/UC refs some of the surrounding text would be useful. Ideally the containing sentence. If not, maybe just a number of words before the tag (important) and a number after (less important).\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What kind of incompletions are there?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Empty fields\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Deleted step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid UC refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"User-defined tags: TODO, TBD.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What causes them in real-life?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Bad refs – Mistakes. Deletion of ref target.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Empty – Don't know/care. Not enough time.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"TODO/TBD – Need to think, need to talk to someone, awaiting external event.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What is the typical lifecycle of such an incompletion?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It occurs, you see it, you ignore it, you resolve or delete it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Can you think of or do you remember any variations?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"No.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Some fields are mandatory? How often does the mandatory-ness change?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Well that's at the discresion of the req manager. It can definitely change over time as the project gets underway.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also if a use case is missing a version or priority that is often considered an incompletion.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"[Field Management]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"“Users will likely need to configure their own UC fields.”\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Why?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Use cases are not set in stone. Teams have their preferences. Somethings work better than others depending on the team and project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How often?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Usually only once per-project. Sometimes fields are modified after ending a few UCs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What will they do if they can't?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Be very dissatisfied with the product. Some teams will refuse to use it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Usually at the beginning of a project when less than 10 UCs have been entered.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Who?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The BA.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a team has a nice setup and needs to redo it for each project they would be unhappy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When you say change existing fields, what kind of changes can you imagine specifically?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Renaming it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Changing its mandatory status.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Changing its position wrt other fields.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When deleting a field, what should happen to its content? [Dev question]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It should be gone from all views.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a field is deleted it has content, should anyone still be able to see it? If so, how?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Well just after deletion it might be nice to see it in the editor so that I can copy & paste bits of it around elsewhere. Otherwise, no.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a field was deleted by mistake, in error or just by bad judgement, what would the consequences be?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Valuable data could be lost. If there are only a few UCs it would be bad, if there were many it could be disasterous.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What are the time/cost/effort implications of said consequences?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Could be absoluetly massive!\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What would you do to remedy the situation?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Would have to either reenter the info from previous copies lying around and/or from BA's memory, likely having to reengage the client.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of a solution?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Find various UCs online and in books with different structures and ensure the system supports creating them with the same or at least very similar structure.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"[Read All UCs & Generate PDF]\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When & why would you want to view/read multiple UCs at once?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. When editing and/or reviewing my UCs to ensure correctness at a larger scope, find problems.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. To print out a subset to give/show someone.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. When performing some other tasks that depends on them. (Design, dev, requirements diagrams)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When & why would you want to print UCs?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. To read and/or review offline.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. To give to someone else to read/review.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. For safe-keeping. Hard copies can be a form of redundancy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How often would you want to perform <answers above>?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. Very often when working on UCs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. Often when working with others.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. Depends on the task. Occasional~Often.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1. Occasional. Offline is a nice break from the PC.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2. Often when working with others.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"3. Not often.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How important is a solution to you? What are the consequences of not having a solution?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Quite important. Without the ability to view and print multiple UCs at once, UCs are trapped in the app. Without the ability to filter these, the ability to view and print multiple UCs at once becomes increasingly useless as the UC count grows.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":403,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T09:11:15.940801Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":76},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":3},{\"gr\":6},{\"gr\":7},{\"gr\":5}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":404,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T09:11:47.273522Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":76},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":75}],\"-\":[{\"gr\":6},{\"gr\":7}]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":405,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T09:12:34.705786Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":77,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Bulk\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":406,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T09:12:40.477841Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":77},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":407,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-01T09:13:46.942939Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":77},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":76}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":408,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:28:53.941414Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":75,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Organisation\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":409,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:29:00.262083Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":75},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Now that the basic system is up and running, something's are gonna be hard as the usage increases. Currently I can write and store and share usecases, as the number of usecases grow looking at them all as a flat list isn't going to make sense. I'm need to organise them somehow, 1) so that the list isn't overwhelming, and 2) because I need that organisation for other purposes.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The first type of organisation or grouping that comes to mind (and need) is versioning. I need to keep track of which usecases are in which version so that when I'm working on that I can narrow my focus to relevant usecases and ignore the rest. Groupings should be arbitrary, I don't want to be restricted to versions. JIRA has issue type, components and more; Github uses labels/tags like AwaitingInfo, Enhancement, Defect, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I was thinking, the real-world system, and real-world model... Ucs are descriptions of interaction. A version has nothing to do with it. It's separate. Versions are their own entities, part of a project schedule. Users should be able to change which Ucs are in which version without opening a UC, or affecting the content of a UC. In real-life the contents of a version can change very quickly and spontaneously.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What's similar? … Affected components (isn't that the actors?). I'm not sure if actors will suffice for this. But I know that grouping Ucs by it would be very important. Different teams of people can be responsible for different components and they will often want to only see Ucs for their own component(s). In real life it's: UC (interaction desc) → multiple components → people. People have their own org strategies (esp. team), components have their own relationships (eg. A and B are part of X).\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Users might just need to group Ucs together. Maybe Ucs 1-8 all relation to a particular function (eg. stock trading)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Priorities are a big one! Similar to versions, fickle and ephemeral, change often, arbitrary strategies/definitions/schemes/approaches. They need an ordering between them (ie. High > med > low). Versions will need that too actually (ie. 1.9 < 1.9.1 < 1.10 < 1.11)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Any organisational units should be applicable to share UC selection. (Eg. Have a share that shows high-pri for 1.x)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Interestingly versions have their own attributes: release date; status/state = pending, in progress, released, in testing; more?) I might want to create a share that shows Ucs for all unreleased versions.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also some org units might have different cardinality restrictions. 1 version might be required, 1+ components might be required. If a UC is missing a version of component a user would probably want to be able to see, identify and correct that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Complication: Use cases are not always implemented in full. It's normal for 90% of a UC to be in scope for version A, and then the remaining 10% to go in version C. Usually this is because parts of the UC depend on another UC that isn't in the same scope. Function requirements are probably atomic enough to be assigned to a single version without issue.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":410,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:29:04.109697Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":75},\"patch\":{\"+\":[],\"-\":[{\"gr\":6}]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":411,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:30:08.091947Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":76},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Secondly, I also need to know which usecases are complete and which still need work. Usecases will often be a work in progress, filled with TODOs and TBDs, empty fields. I need a way to access the state of (in)completeness across my all usecases without having to click and manually read each one.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":412,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:30:24.363705Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":75,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Organisation: initial\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":413,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:30:48.188684Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":76},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":6}],\"-\":[{\"gr\":75},{\"gr\":3},{\"gr\":5}]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":414,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:31:37.644004Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":77,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Organisation: follow-up\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":415,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:31:51.706665Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":77},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":75}],\"-\":[{\"gr\":76}]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":416,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:32:34.620883Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":77},\"value\":[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[17/12/2013: Continuing on...]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I was reading about Feature Trees. It's a very simple method of organisation and mind-mapping. You start with the project/app in the center, draw a line out of it to a box which is a feature. Now along that line draw protruding lines (like brnahces on a tree) which are the use cases required to implement, or just pertaining to, the feature. Simple and effective. (Additionally, the book recommends writing functional requirements underneath the UCs but that's a bit verbose. Although a dynamic and interactive diagram might be perfect! Scroll around, zoom into an area, see the functional requirements appear. Cool.)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Anyway, I thought about this a little more and Features are just collections of smaller capabilities. They fit the same model described above. They have an n:n mapping with UCs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Acutally, they can have their own priority which would probably be either 1) a multiplier to their children UCs' priorities, or 2) a parent priority that would take precedence over the children's priorities. Interesting. Once these were in-place some nice graphs might be doable, I'm imagining a table or grid, versions at the top, features on the left, and then colours boxes in the middle overlapping versions and... wait that doesn't make sense, there's no overlap. It would just be like the Major Features & Release Plan in V&S docs. Well maybe priority could be introduced. For some reason I imagine different coloured semi-transparent bars overlapping being extremely useful as a visualisation tool. Coming from my subconcious or gut, I'll need to think about that later. One thing is for sure though, automatic or easily generatable diagrams will get lots of points with potential users I think. They appeal. Good diagrams are orders of magnitude more efficient at conveying information that text. They're usually harder to manually draw and maintain than text. Even if I invent my own diagrams, they should provide a lot of business value.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Where was I? Organisation. Yes! Well Features are another organisational device, they may have their own (arbitrary) attributes, how their attributes affect UC attributes (if at all) will likely be arbitrary.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When the system gets versions, I would to see a list of versions and as first-class list items. What I mean is, unlike Github and JIRA where you see a list of issues and then apply filters, I want to just see a list of versions, maybe with a little footnote for each one like “23 UCs” or something. Similar to how at the moment you log in, you see projects, click a project you see UCs. I want to see Versions, click, see UCs. I would like the same thing with Features. It would probably be good to be able to do it for all units of organisation. The ability to do it with multiple levels (eg. ver → component) or maybe matrix/filter style would be the trick!\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Two of the most important project goals are simplicity and ease. Therefore the following must be considered:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Sensible and intuitive defaults.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Effort to use.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Effort to learn, understand how to modify.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Separate and minimise intertwined functions & responsibilities.\"}]]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"[Just went and wrote Requirements/project-attributes.ods]\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Ok, later I should run all my requirements through my project-attributes doc and customise the design.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also how will these organisational units affect publish-views? Should they be present? Toggleable?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will they affect UCE also? Lots of people like Priority in its own field.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"How will these affect UC revision?\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":417,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:32:50.289664Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":76,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Issues: initial\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":418,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:33:12.462268Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":78,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":419,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:33:16.145089Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":78,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Read All UCs & Generate PDF\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":420,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:33:26.187087Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":78},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"I didn't put too much thought into these two functions when I built them into the prototype.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I originally wanted the features for the following reasons:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"So I could see/confirm the layout/markup before sharing/printing.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"So I could read through and review all my UCs.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"I see the two random buttons in the prototype as a problem now because:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"You can't filter the UCs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"You can't add a title & preface.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Actually I think I need the same thing as a share, except with the password. Probably overkill saving the “view” or whatnot. Maybe I could be [main] → [filter] ↔ [view] → [pdf]. Something like that would then allow anon users to filter shares they look at and generate a pdf too. Might be useful. Guessing...\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":421,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:33:36.256046Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":78},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
