    "{\"#\":444,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:41:57.647811Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":82},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":445,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:46:03.429638Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":82},\"value\":[{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How do you deal with this situation currently?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Two ways:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"View all use cases and manually scan text for keywords like TODO, TBD. If using MS Word I normally highlight in red so they stand out.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Keep a separate table of pending tasks.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How will you deal with it until an implementation is provided?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"One of the two ways above. Because the UCE doesn't allow me to colour text, I might even deliberately input invalid refs so that I have something red so my eyes see it fast.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Who is this important to? Why?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The UC editor and reviewer.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It's important because the issues these TODO tags represent need to addressed and not forgotten. Because the BA/reviewer will read multiple revisions of a UC, they naturally start to skim making it very easy to overlook important gaps in the requirements.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What will they do after determining completeness?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"If complete, maybe share for review, print it out maybe. Alert someone.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering empty fields?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Fill them in or enter a TODO/TBD with additional info.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering placeholders?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Try to edit the fields and resolve the incompletions.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"People could be happy with certain fields being empty which would yield false positives. At least in their mind empty fields could be of less value than TODOs so they wouldn't want to wade through a sea of empty-field errors looking for those few TODOs.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How often would it be used?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Very often. Tags would be added nearly every time the UCE is opened for new requirements.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"After requirements start to settle the incompletion-overview function would be used regularly until all were gone.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When would it be used?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"All the time until the end of a project.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When you say you want to see all incompletions in context without having to open each UC...\"}]},{\"h5\":[{\"lit\":\"- why is this important?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The not-wanting-to-open-UC part is obvious. Much effort.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The context part... well I was just thinking of diffs actually. Hmm, well the incompletions just need enough info to make sense without seeing the entire UC. Otherwise displaying them all in a nice list will lose its value if the user then has to open a UC to understand it.\"},{\"h5\":[{\"lit\":\"- what would happen if you couldn't see them in context?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"User would have to open containing UC; no point having a nice summary.\"},{\"h5\":[{\"lit\":\"- what do you expect to see when you say context? How much context?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"• You'd definitely want to see the UC name, and containing field name for all incompletions.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"If TODOs, TBDs etc are able to include additional data, that data should be displayed.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If not the entire field would need to be displayed.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"For invalid step/UC refs some of the surrounding text would be useful. Ideally the containing sentence. If not, maybe just a number of words before the tag (important) and a number after (less important).\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What kind of incompletions are there?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Empty fields\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Deleted step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid UC refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"User-defined tags: TODO, TBD.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What causes them in real-life?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Bad refs – Mistakes. Deletion of ref target.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Empty – Don't know/care. Not enough time.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"TODO/TBD – Need to think, need to talk to someone, awaiting external event.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What is the typical lifecycle of such an incompletion?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It occurs, you see it, you ignore it, you resolve or delete it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Can you think of or do you remember any variations?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"No.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Some fields are mandatory? How often does the mandatory-ness change?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Well that's at the discresion of the req manager. It can definitely change over time as the project gets underway.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also if a use case is missing a version or priority that is often considered an incompletion.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":446,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:46:36.608915Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":82},\"value\":[{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How do you deal with this situation currently?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Two ways:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"View all use cases and manually scan text for keywords like TODO, TBD. If using MS Word I normally highlight in red so they stand out.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Keep a separate table of pending tasks.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How will you deal with it until an implementation is provided?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"One of the two ways above. Because the UCE doesn't allow me to colour text, I might even deliberately input invalid refs so that I have something red so my eyes see it fast.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Who is this important to? Why?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The UC editor and reviewer.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It's important because the issues these TODO tags represent need to addressed and not forgotten. Because the BA/reviewer will read multiple revisions of a UC, they naturally start to skim making it very easy to overlook important gaps in the requirements.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What will they do after determining completeness?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"If complete, maybe share for review, print it out maybe. Alert someone.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering empty fields?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Fill them in or enter a TODO/TBD with additional info.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What will they do after discovering placeholders?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Try to edit the fields and resolve the incompletions.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"People could be happy with certain fields being empty which would yield false positives. At least in their mind empty fields could be of less value than TODOs so they wouldn't want to wade through a sea of empty-field errors looking for those few TODOs.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How often would it be used?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Very often. Tags would be added nearly every time the UCE is opened for new requirements.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"After requirements start to settle the incompletion-overview function would be used regularly until all were gone.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When would it be used?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"All the time until the end of a project.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When you say you want to see all incompletions in context without having to open each UC...\"}]},{\"h5\":[{\"lit\":\"- why is this important?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The not-wanting-to-open-UC part is obvious. Much effort.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The context part... well I was just thinking of diffs actually. Hmm, well the incompletions just need enough info to make sense without seeing the entire UC. Otherwise displaying them all in a nice list will lose its value if the user then has to open a UC to understand it.\"},{\"h5\":[{\"lit\":\"- what would happen if you couldn't see them in context?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"User would have to open containing UC; no point having a nice summary.\"},{\"h5\":[{\"lit\":\"- what do you expect to see when you say context? How much context?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"You'd definitely want to see the UC name, and containing field name for all incompletions.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If TODOs, TBDs etc are able to include additional data, that data should be displayed.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If not the entire field would need to be displayed.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"For invalid step/UC refs some of the surrounding text would be useful. Ideally the containing sentence. If not, maybe just a number of words before the tag (important) and a number after (less important).\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What kind of incompletions are there?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Empty fields\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Deleted step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid step refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Invalid UC refs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"User-defined tags: TODO, TBD.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What causes them in real-life?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Bad refs – Mistakes. Deletion of ref target.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Empty – Don't know/care. Not enough time.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"TODO/TBD – Need to think, need to talk to someone, awaiting external event.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is the typical lifecycle of such an incompletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It occurs, you see it, you ignore it, you resolve or delete it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of or do you remember any variations?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"No.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Some fields are mandatory? How often does the mandatory-ness change?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Well that's at the discresion of the req manager. It can definitely change over time as the project gets underway.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also if a use case is missing a version or priority that is often considered an incompletion.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":447,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:47:28.395116Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":83,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":448,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:47:43.230598Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":83,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Field Customisation: Q&A\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":449,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:47:46.987298Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":83},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":450,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:48:14.564910Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":83},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":80}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":451,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:48:40.793793Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":83},\"value\":[{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"“Users will likely need to configure their own UC fields.” -- Why?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Use cases are not set in stone. Teams have their preferences. Somethings work better than others depending on the team and project.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How often?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Usually only once per-project. Sometimes fields are modified after ending a few UCs.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What will they do if they can't?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Be very dissatisfied with the product. Some teams will refuse to use it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Usually at the beginning of a project when less than 10 UCs have been entered.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Who?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The BA.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What problems could this feature create?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"If a team has a nice setup and needs to redo it for each project they would be unhappy.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When you say change existing fields, what kind of changes can you imagine specifically?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Renaming it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Changing its mandatory status.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Changing its position wrt other fields.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When deleting a field, what should happen to its content? [Dev question]\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It should be gone from all views.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If a field is deleted it has content, should anyone still be able to see it? If so, how?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Well just after deletion it might be nice to see it in the editor so that I can copy & paste bits of it around elsewhere. Otherwise, no.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If a field was deleted by mistake, in error or just by bad judgement, what would the consequences be?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Valuable data could be lost. If there are only a few UCs it would be bad, if there were many it could be disasterous.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What are the time/cost/effort implications of said consequences?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Could be absoluetly massive!\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do to remedy the situation?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Would have to either reenter the info from previous copies lying around and/or from BA's memory, likely having to reengage the client.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of a solution?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Find various UCs online and in books with different structures and ensure the system supports creating them with the same or at least very similar structure.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":452,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:48:50.194511Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":84,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":453,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:49:00.961421Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":84,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Read All UCs & Generate PDF: Q&A\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":454,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:49:19.665853Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":84},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":78}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":455,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:49:27.004459Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":84},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":456,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:55:17.770295Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":84},\"value\":[{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When & why would you want to view/read multiple UCs at once?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"1. When editing and/or reviewing my UCs to ensure correctness at a larger scope, find problems.\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"To print out a subset to give/show someone.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"When performing some other tasks that depends on them. (Design, dev, requirements diagrams)\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When & why would you want to print UCs?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"1. To read and/or review offline.\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"To give to someone else to read/review.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"For safe-keeping. Hard copies can be a form of redundancy.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How often would you want to perform <answers above>?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Very often when working on UCs.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Often when working with others.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Depends on the task. Occasional~Often.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"+\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Occasional. Offline is a nice break from the PC.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Often when working with others.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Not often.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How important is a solution to you? What are the consequences of not having a solution?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Quite important. Without the ability to view and print multiple UCs at once, UCs are trapped in the app. Without the ability to filter these, the ability to view and print multiple UCs at once becomes increasingly useless as the UC count grows.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":457,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:55:28.206845Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":85,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":458,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:55:41.476897Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":85,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Templates: prelim\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":459,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:55:47.240956Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":85},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":4}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":460,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:55:55.208868Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":85},\"patch\":{\"+\":[13],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":461,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:56:24.829620Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":85},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Right, well there are two things under the template umbrella that I'd like.\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Viewing an explaination of how to fill-in a UC field.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Seeing other examples of the field's values.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"First one. Because we're not all experts sometimes when writing a UC you forget exactly what is supposed to be in a field, exactly where the borders of its scope lie, or maybe there are some important constraints on that field, maybe you'd like some tips on how to write effective values for it. For these reasons it's useful to use or refer to a template. When teams are using Word (or whatever) instead of ShipReq they will often create a template in Word with instructions on what to write in each field. Using ShipReq at the moment, you lose that. When I'm writing a UC FV I'd like to be able to see the instructions for that field for more clarity or help.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Second one. For all the reasons previously stated, in addition to looking at template instructions when stuck, people also commonly go and look at other UCs to see how they were filled out. Consequentially it would be useful if I were working on “Frequency of Use”, to be able to see “Frequency of Use” values in other UCs within the project. I'm not sure about various revisions, probably the latest revision would be best because older revisions could have bad examples that were later fixed. As for seeing values from other UCs outside of the project... I'm not sure. This would also be nice because I might like to copy & paste a value from another UC then change a word or two.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What about deleted UCs? Should I be able to view their FVs? Might not hurt. Might be useful.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So all of that's from a UC Writers perspective. From a maintainer's or head-BA's perspective, I'd also need the ability to customise the template and use it across different projects. I'd want to go in, edit the template value for field X, apply it and then have Writers see it the next time they write a new, or edit an existing UC.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":462,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:57:12.101724Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":86,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":463,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:57:14.455015Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":86},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Grouping names: what are your thoughts on two different groupings with the same name in a project? Would you expect that to happen? If so, can you explain why and give an example? Finally how would you cope if same names weren't allowed?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I think it would be incredibly rare. The only scenario I can think of would be if there were two trees of groupings with the same nodes but named differently at the top, so like “Dev Status” and “Test Status” could both a grouping called Pending. If it were applied like a tag/level then “Pending” on its own would be useless without context, it would need to be “ Dev Status: Pending”.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If it were not permitted, I don't think it would be a problem. That would just mean that every now and then one would have to add a little more description to a name. No biggie.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Grouping names will need a length limit. What's the longest name you would need?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"“Version: Unreleased and/or pending allocation”\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"“Feature: Generic artifact storage (DOC, PDF, PNG, XLS)”\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Groupings can sometimes apply to a portion of a use case, but not the entire use case. Can you think of an example? If groupings could only be applied to a use case as a whole, what impact would that have? How would you work around it? How much would the ability be worth to you?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When a use cases has many steps, it's not uncommon for a most steps to be implemented in version A, with the few remaining steps being scheduled for a later version, usually because they are dependent on another feature that is out-of-scope for version A. In this case Version, Status, and Feature are examples of groupings that would apply to different parts of the use case differently.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If they could only be applied to the whole... I guess there would be two strategies:\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"1) Apply only the groupings that apply to the majority and omit the others. The problem with that would be that someone looking at the v2.0 grouping wouldn't be aware that the UC was part of it. Which is bad.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"2) Apply everything relevant to any part of the UC. The groupings would make sense but then anyone reading the UC will likely not understand why it has multiple versions, which steps belong to the second version. To avoid this frustration users would probably start using one of the UC text fields to describe the situation. An idea might be to attach comments to groupings when they are applied, e.g. I would apply v1.0 without comment, then v2.0 with a comment saying “Applies to [3.5.c] only”. Of course if such a mechanism were implemented, then the step ref in the comment should be kept in sync when the label changes.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It'd certainly be nice to have but there are more interesting features pending. With the above workaround (2) I'd probably be well content.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Actually, being a detailed kinda guy, if I were able to apply groupings to steps I'd probably spend too much time mucking around with it to make sure it was always accurate.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Currently use cases have a revision number. What specifically is that revision number used for? Why does anyone care? Should the revision number increase when a grouping is applied or unapplied? Would there be issues if the revision number didn't change? Do you foresee any issues with the revision number incrementing by 1 when a grouping is applied or unapplied?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The revision number is used when comparing UC copies to determine which is more recent (up-to-date) than the other. Admittedly I also use it to gauge amount of revision and/or complexity, which isn't a good idea; correcting a typo and adding 100 steps both only increase the number by 1.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The revision should definitely increase if a grouping displayed in a field changes. If the content of the UC stays the same then ideally it wouldn't change, else you might confuse people implying a change only for them not to be able to find one.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If the rev no increased by 1 when a grouping is (un)applied then that would be fine so long as the grouping change were discernable in publish-mode or when exported.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a grouping were renamed, for use cases with that grouping applied, what would happen if the revision number wasn't updated?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The revision number is basically a contract that users can depend on to say “I'm looking at rev XX, you're holding a copy of XX you printed last week, we can rely on both our presentations of the UC being identical.” Anything that violates that should change the revision number, this includes field changes, grouping changes (renamed), grouping applications. If a grouping change is invisible (eg. grouping description) fine, but a name change needs to update the revision number too, else it's a loophole for people to break the revision-number contract.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Would you ever want to copy groupings between projects? If so, why? Please give an example scenario. What would the consequences be if you were unable to do so?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Sure, I could create a tree of priority groupings, could/should/must, with detailed descriptions including examples and rules. That would be tedious to redo manually, I'd see myself copying that for every new project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Being unable to copy select groupings (I don't want to copy all) would mean I need to recreate stuff manually. For large and/or detailed grouping trees, YUK. Waste of time. Annoying. I want to focus on real work.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a grouping that is applied to use cases and displayed as a field is deleted, what would happen if it were deleted automatically from said use cases? What would happen if the revision number of those use cases remained the same? What would happen if the deletion was a mistake?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If I'm deleting a grouping I would expect it to disappear from UCs. Revision number: see contract.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If the deletion were a mistake I would need to recreate it, then reapply it. If I deleted just a grouping tree node, then recreation and reapplication aren't that big a deal (so long as I remember how it should be applied.) If I delete an entire tree then it's much harder. Very, very annoying. But realistically how often would someone accidentally delete a grouping or change their mind later? It'd be pretty rare. If the grouping were a user-specified though, they'd be fucked.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Hard deletion here would introduce a lack of consistency around deletion semantics. Users can delete populated UC fields and recover them, it wouldn't be unfair for them to assume the same practice were possible here.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If a grouping that is applied to use cases and not displayed as a field is deleted, what would happen if it were deleted automatically from said use cases? What would happen if the revision number of those use cases remained the same? What would happen if the deletion was a mistake?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Same as above. Not being displayed as a field implies that it's simply transient metadata for organisational (or other) purposes but I wouldn't want to gamble on that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What is the deal with groupings that aren't specifically linked to fields anyway? Will they be displayed in export/publish mode?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When using groupings to filter requirements, have you ever needed to see everything without a certain grouping? (i.e. NOT) Can you foresee a problem if this ability were not provided?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Sure, anything that's not status:complete, anything that's not priority:low, anything that doesn't have a priority yet.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It depends on the interface, as a workaround you'd select everything else except the grouping you want to negate. It would be at least slightly annoying. Tremendously so for larger grouping trees.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Can you please give some examples of multiple-grouping criteria you would use to search/filter requirements?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Easy: version 1.0 AND (priority critical OR high).\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If groupings were specifiable as trees (with nodes being allowed multiple parents), what would the impact be if you couldn't specify relationships between different grouping trees? Examples? How would you work around these scenarios?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Here are previously collected examples:\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Version|Feature → Status I can live without.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Feature → Priority is nice to see but really the app is fine without it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Feature → Version would be quite useful. Workarounds: 1) manually change version of everything in a given feature. 2) Cheat and put Features in the Version grouping tree, either is children of the target version, or as a parent node with the target version symlink as a child. Something like that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What would be cool would be if I applied MF-05 to a UC, and the Version field was automatically populated with v1.2, that would be AWESOME.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":464,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:57:23.572653Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":86,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Organisation: Q&A\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":465,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:57:31.353343Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":86},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":81}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":466,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T02:57:43.525988Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":86},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":467,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:02:58.617292Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":86},\"value\":[{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Grouping names: what are your thoughts on two different groupings with the same name in a project? Would you expect that to happen? If so, can you explain why and give an example? Finally how would you cope if same names weren't allowed?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I think it would be incredibly rare. The only scenario I can think of would be if there were two trees of groupings with the same nodes but named differently at the top, so like “Dev Status” and “Test Status” could both a grouping called Pending. If it were applied like a tag/level then “Pending” on its own would be useless without context, it would need to be “ Dev Status: Pending”.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If it were not permitted, I don't think it would be a problem. That would just mean that every now and then one would have to add a little more description to a name. No biggie.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Grouping names will need a length limit. What's the longest name you would need?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"“Version: Unreleased and/or pending allocation”\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"“Feature: Generic artifact storage (DOC, PDF, PNG, XLS)”\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Groupings can sometimes apply to a portion of a use case, but not the entire use case. Can you think of an example? If groupings could only be applied to a use case as a whole, what impact would that have? How would you work around it? How much would the ability be worth to you?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"When a use cases has many steps, it's not uncommon for a most steps to be implemented in version A, with the few remaining steps being scheduled for a later version, usually because they are dependent on another feature that is out-of-scope for version A. In this case Version, Status, and Feature are examples of groupings that would apply to different parts of the use case differently.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If they could only be applied to the whole... I guess there would be two strategies:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Apply only the groupings that apply to the majority and omit the others. The problem with that would be that someone looking at the v2.0 grouping wouldn't be aware that the UC was part of it. Which is bad.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Apply everything relevant to any part of the UC. The groupings would make sense but then anyone reading the UC will likely not understand why it has multiple versions, which steps belong to the second version. To avoid this frustration users would probably start using one of the UC text fields to describe the situation. An idea might be to attach comments to groupings when they are applied, e.g. I would apply v1.0 without comment, then v2.0 with a comment saying “Applies to [3.5.c] only”. Of course if such a mechanism were implemented, then the step ref in the comment should be kept in sync when the label changes.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"It'd certainly be nice to have but there are more interesting features pending. With the above workaround (2) I'd probably be well content.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Actually, being a detailed kinda guy, if I were able to apply groupings to steps I'd probably spend too much time mucking around with it to make sure it was always accurate.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Currently use cases have a revision number. What specifically is that revision number used for? Why does anyone care? Should the revision number increase when a grouping is applied or unapplied? Would there be issues if the revision number didn't change? Do you foresee any issues with the revision number incrementing by 1 when a grouping is applied or unapplied?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The revision number is used when comparing UC copies to determine which is more recent (up-to-date) than the other. Admittedly I also use it to gauge amount of revision and/or complexity, which isn't a good idea; correcting a typo and adding 100 steps both only increase the number by 1.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The revision should definitely increase if a grouping displayed in a field changes. If the content of the UC stays the same then ideally it wouldn't change, else you might confuse people implying a change only for them not to be able to find one.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If the rev no increased by 1 when a grouping is (un)applied then that would be fine so long as the grouping change were discernable in publish-mode or when exported.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If a grouping were renamed, for use cases with that grouping applied, what would happen if the revision number wasn't updated?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The revision number is basically a contract that users can depend on to say “I'm looking at rev XX, you're holding a copy of XX you printed last week, we can rely on both our presentations of the UC being identical.” Anything that violates that should change the revision number, this includes field changes, grouping changes (renamed), grouping applications. If a grouping change is invisible (eg. grouping description) fine, but a name change needs to update the revision number too, else it's a loophole for people to break the revision-number contract.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Would you ever want to copy groupings between projects? If so, why? Please give an example scenario. What would the consequences be if you were unable to do so?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Sure, I could create a tree of priority groupings, could/should/must, with detailed descriptions including examples and rules. That would be tedious to redo manually, I'd see myself copying that for every new project.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Being unable to copy select groupings (I don't want to copy all) would mean I need to recreate stuff manually. For large and/or detailed grouping trees, YUK. Waste of time. Annoying. I want to focus on real work.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If a grouping that is applied to use cases and \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"displayed as a field\"}]},{\"lit\":\" is deleted, what would happen if it were deleted automatically from said use cases? What would happen if the revision number of those use cases remained the same? What would happen if the deletion was a mistake?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"If I'm deleting a grouping I would expect it to disappear from UCs. Revision number: see contract.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If the deletion were a mistake I would need to recreate it, then reapply it. If I deleted just a grouping tree node, then recreation and reapplication aren't that big a deal (so long as I remember how it should be applied.) If I delete an entire tree then it's much harder. Very, very annoying. But realistically how often would someone accidentally delete a grouping or change their mind later? It'd be pretty rare. If the grouping were a user-specified though, they'd be fucked.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Hard deletion here would introduce a lack of consistency around deletion semantics. Users can delete populated UC fields and recover them, it wouldn't be unfair for them to assume the same practice were possible here.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If a grouping that is applied to use cases and \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"not displayed as a field\"}]},{\"lit\":\" is deleted, what would happen if it were deleted automatically from said use cases? What would happen if the revision number of those use cases remained the same? What would happen if the deletion was a mistake?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same as above. Not being displayed as a field implies that it's simply transient metadata for organisational (or other) purposes but I wouldn't want to gamble on that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What is the deal with groupings that aren't specifically linked to fields anyway? Will they be displayed in export/publish mode?\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When using groupings to filter requirements, have you ever needed to see everything without a certain grouping? (i.e. NOT) Can you foresee a problem if this ability were not provided?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Sure, anything that's not status:complete, anything that's not priority:low, anything that doesn't have a priority yet.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It depends on the interface, as a workaround you'd select everything else except the grouping you want to negate. It would be at least slightly annoying. Tremendously so for larger grouping trees.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you please give some examples of multiple-grouping criteria you would use to search/filter requirements?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Easy: version 1.0 AND (priority critical OR high).\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If groupings were specifiable as trees (with nodes being allowed multiple parents), what would the impact be if you couldn't specify relationships between different grouping trees? Examples? How would you work around these scenarios?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Here are previously collected examples:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Version \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"has a\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Status\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Feature \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"has a\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Priority\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Feature \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"has a\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Status\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Component \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"is owned by\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Team\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Feature \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"scheduled for\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Version\"}]]},{\"ul\":[[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Version|Feature → Status\"}]},{\"lit\":\" -- I can live without.\"}],[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Feature → Priority\"}]},{\"lit\":\" is nice to see but really the app is fine without it.\"}],[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Feature → Version\"}]},{\"lit\":\" would be quite useful. Workarounds: 1) manually change version of everything in a given feature. 2) Cheat and put * Features in the Version grouping tree, either is children of the target version, or as a parent node with the target version symlink as a child. Something like that.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What would be cool would be if I applied MF-05 to a UC, and the Version field was automatically populated with v1.2, that would be AWESOME.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":468,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:03:26.803330Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":87,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":469,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:03:36.668106Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":87,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Low-Level Requirements: prelim\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":470,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:08:45.476693Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":87},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Low-level requirements are critical in the requirements process.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"My assumption is that they are atomic because they are nearly always stored as a flat list with each requirement having its own ID. Actually in \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Software Requirements 3\"}]},{\"lit\":\", it says that each (LL) requirement should be independent. A problem (I feel) with this is that you end up with lots of requirements that are very long and only different to other requirements by a word or two. Examples:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"The user shall be able to allocate liability of a financial event by specifying a ratio.\"}]}],[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"The user shall be able to allocate liability of a financial event by specifying percentages.\"}]}],[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"The user shall be able to allocate liability of a financial event by specifying prices.\"}]}]]},{\"lit\":\"People usually use Excel for this so whatever solution we come up with shouldn't be a worse UX than using Excel. Things we normally do in Excel are:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"see a bunch in a list and move the cursor around editing them all.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"filter rows by some sort of criteria\"}],[{\"lit\":\"mass search/replace\"}],[{\"lit\":\"copy, paste, edit\"}],[{\"lit\":\"add/remove columns\"}],[{\"lit\":\"change the type of a requirement (eg. FR to CO)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"incomplete stuff I can colour red\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Excel works quite well actually. The problems that I have using it are:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Have to manually manage req IDs (unique, increment per type)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Keeping track of last-updated date. (revision would be nice as well)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Linking to MFs (grouping by?)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Some reqs arise as a result of two or more features intersecting, this is sort of hard to represent. What I'm doing in one project is having two MF columns, one for strongly-related, one for weakly-related. So far it works well. In some cases I even put a dash for strongly-related and the only feature in weakly-related which was an interesting side-effect.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"No way to reference other requirements although I don't remember doing that much. (wait...ever?)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Have to restrain myself adding columns bcos too many scrolls half the stuff off the screen.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Have to store UCs which are already stored elsewhere. Then of course they go out-of-date.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"It's annoying having to type “shall be able to” so often.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Wow, I think that might be all these is to it. Having them recorded is the important part. What else?...\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"How they are used later is they are filtered and copied into docs (like SRS).\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Eventually each should ideally by approved and signed-off.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"It would be good to scan them all for ambiguous language.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"The same incompletions functionality that applies to use cases should apply here as well.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I used to imagine having a checklist per requirement that I would tick during review. The attributes in the checklist come from the \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"SR3\"}]},{\"lit\":\" book and they are: complete, correct, feasible, necessary, prioritised, unambiguous, verifiable.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Looking at examples in Appendix C of \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"SR3\"}]},{\"lit\":\", I note the following:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Other LL requirements are indeed referenced regularly, often Business Rules. An example of an FR reference is \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"“If \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"[Order.Done]\"}]},{\"lit\":\" fails, the COS shall roll back ...”\"}]}],[{\"lit\":\"Functional Requirements \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"do not\"}]},{\"lit\":\" use a FR-n ID system! Nor are they flat. They are instead hierarchical and named. Example:\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"  Order.Menu:  Viewing a menu\\n   .Date:      The COS shall display a menu for the date that the Patron specified.\\n   .Available: The menu for the specified date shall display only those food items ...\"}}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm seeing some 3-letter requirement-type IDs. (AVL for Availability Requirement)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"This guy combines multiple things into the same requirement. Example:\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"The COS shall display the remaining available delivery times for the meal date. The COS shall allow the Patron to require one of the delivery times shown, to change the order to be picked up in the cafeteria, or to cancel the order.\"}]}]]},{\"lit\":\"The difference between FR-\"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"n\"}]},{\"lit\":\" and text-tree-style functional requirements is disconcerting but I wonder if there's a way I could merge the two instead of anyone having to make the distinction up-front (and stick to it). In the text-based scenario stable IDs would be required under-the-covers; in the numeric scenario the other style might be achieved by groupings and a mechanism to make some FRs children of others.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Requirement-types are arbitrary and need to be customisable. I need to be able to add & remove types, set type mnemonics, modify fields (columns) per type.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":471,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:10:39.937938Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":87},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":12}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
