    "{\"#\":485,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:17:56.961803Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":90},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":87}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":486,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:18:03.778099Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":90},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":487,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T03:24:01.298513Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":90},\"value\":[{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Does anyone ever \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"delete LL reqs\"}]},{\"lit\":\"? What else needs to happen when a req is deleted? What about references to it?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Yes. Normally I just grey it out. The ID isn't recoverable. ID should always point to the same logic requirement. As for references, if there are any I guess I'd delete them. Sometimes it might make sense to keep them. Eg. “Blah blah. (Replaces FR-23)”\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If references to a deleted ref were around, would you need to know about it? Why? What if the system didn't show you where they were?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd always want to be alerted to it, yes. Cos those refs would usually be invalid. If they system didn't show me, it'd be annoying to manually check through everything and I would end up missing stuff.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Does anyone ever need to \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"see\"}]},{\"lit\":\" what \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"a deleted req\"}]},{\"lit\":\" was? Why? What happens if they can't?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Yes. There could be an offline reference to it, or I may want to see what it was to undelete it. If I can't, that would mean it was gone forever, right? That's bad. (See next Q)\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Does anyone ever \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"restore a deleted req\"}]},{\"lit\":\"? Why? What happens if they can't?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Definitely. Requirements change, scope changes and those changes often cause requirements to be deleted and then later restored and tweaked. If data were lost, that would be terrible. Unacceptable.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"removing a requirement-type\"}]},{\"lit\":\", please opine about the following effects:\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Associated requirements are deleted.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Associated requirements are moved into a different req type. If no other req types exist, prevent operation.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If associated requirements exist, prevent operation.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"If I were deleting a requirement-type that would imply I was reorganising. Consequentially I wouldn't want anything automatically deleted (bye bye option #1). If it were very easy (as it should be) to change requirements' types in bulk then #3 works. #2 seems like a nice fallback but it's a shortcut which implies that it isn't easy to change requirements' types in bulk. That's bad. I thought we made it easy in \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":7}},{\"lit\":\", it should be like that.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why is vertical scrolling ok but \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"horizontal scrolling\"}]},{\"lit\":\" so bad?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Vertical scrolling is normally fine because you scroll entire reqs on and off the screen. With horizontal scrolling you end up scrolling useful info about your focused req off the screen, not to mention the entire screen is then full of less-useful info about \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"all\"}]},{\"lit\":\" reqs, most of which you don't care about.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Please list \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"custom columns and attributes\"}]},{\"lit\":\" that LL reqs sometimes get. Please also list ones that are specific to certain requirement-types.\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"MF        The primary Major-Feature driving the requirement.\\nMF-β      A Major-Feature that also contributes to the need for the requirement.\\nCreated   When the req was first written.\\nUpdated   When the req was last updated.\\nVersion   The version in which the requirement is scheduled.\\nPriority  Obvious.\\nExample   An example of the requirement being applied.\\nNotes     Any additional information that clarifies the requirement.\\nTODO      Reasons why the requirement needs more work.\"}},{\"lit\":\"Business Rules have columns:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Type of rule\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Static or dynamic\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Source\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"These look like they could be accomplished by groupings (MF-07) but does one lose something doing it that way instead of a table with dedicated columns?\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why do you \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"need custom columns/attributes\"}]},{\"lit\":\"? What would bother you if you had to store all of the info that you'd normally store in custom columns, in the req description?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I need the columns because reqs have important attributes (RWM) and I need them recorded.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"When it's in a grid/table, it's\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Easy to see when something is missing.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Easier to comprehend. Less cognative effort required because I don't need to read to find the info I need.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Some columns are not necessary to the reader. The reader may read them once and from that time onwards the req makes enough sense on its own. They provide additional context that is required for less than 50% of reads.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When would you ever want to assign a req \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"multiple semantic-IDs\"}]},{\"lit\":\"? Why? What would the effect be if the system didn't allow this?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"When a requirement exists in an intersection between two or more features. If the system didn't allow this then either 1) I'd have to scan some other column to find secondarily-related reqs (eg. MF-β), or 2) I'd have to use refs to point a reader to the other requirements.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When sorting requirements, please provide \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"sorting examples\"}]},{\"lit\":\". When would you want to sort? After you accomplish your task, when would you need to sort next?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"• Sort by updated-date. When reviewing. Afterwards I'd restore the default sort order.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Sort by MF . semantic-IDs . numeric-ID. When editing to check organisation. Afterwards nothing; this is my default sort order.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Sort by desc. When looking for duplicates. Afterwards I'd restore the default sort order.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When sorting, if you were unable to select \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"DESC order\"}]},{\"lit\":\" instead of ASC, how would that affect you? How important would that be to you?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Don't really care. Look up instead of down. Although it might annoy me with a priority column. Even then, not very much I don't think.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When sorting is active and you change the content of a requirement which puts it out-of-order, should the view \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"reorder immediately\"}]},{\"lit\":\"?\"}]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"SI: It doesn't, but a little button appears saying “Out-of-order. Re-sort” which user can click when done.\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Normally immediate resorting'd be awesome, instant feedback and all that. Only foreseeable problem its when I want to fill in semantic-IDs for a bunch of reqs in a row. I'd find it really annoying to have to refind the next blank req I was up to before the resorting moved my cursor (if that's how it works).... then again, if resorting happened after the cursor move that'd be fine.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When reqs are displayed hierarchically using their semantic-IDs, sometimes there are \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"rows that serve just as a header\"}]},{\"lit\":\" for their children without being a req themselves. If this behaviour were not supported how would it affect you? How strongly would you feel when you realised it was missing? How would you work around it?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"This behaviour is recommended in More About Software Requirements in the section discussing child/parent requirements. Granted that's not exactly for semantic-IDs but it's the same principal. If it were not supported it could lead to children reqs contradicting parent reqs, or reqs that aren't actually reqs being used to hack the system and achieve the same effect.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When viewing a list of reqs, for each req on the screen, do you \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"need to see every column/attr\"}]},{\"lit\":\"? For each column please state your preference, and what the consequence would be if you could only see it for one req at a time.\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"MF        Meh. I'll have semantic IDs. Technically out-of-scope for now anyway.\\nMF-β      Meh. I'll have semantic IDs. Technically out-of-scope for now anyway.\\nCreated   Normally meh, but matters when I'm sorting by it. If I'm sorting by it that means I'm interested in the timeline, what? I have to click each one? That's annoying.\\nUpdated   As above.\\nVersion   I wouldn't mind so long as I have that nice grouping applier & view promised in MF-07.\\nPriority  As above.\\nExample   Ok not to see.\\nNotes     Ok not to see.\\nTODO      Annoying unless I can easily go from LL-req editor to list of incompletions in LL-reqs.\"}}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":488,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T10:57:39.128012Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":91,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":489,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T10:57:53.507376Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":91,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"High-Level Requirements: Q&A\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":490,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T10:58:08.127276Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":91},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":491,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T11:00:27.899745Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":91},\"value\":[{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How do you currently use MFs?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Comprehend what the project will do/provide.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Communicate the intended direction of the project (roadmap).\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Break work down into smaller units.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Plan versions. (eg. MF-1,2,3 in v1.0, MF-7 in v1.1, etc.)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Find missing requirements by analysing feature/scope intersections.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Organise low-level requirements.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How do you currently use FEs?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Actually, as requirements in the strict sense, I don't. However they are present in concept throughout the entire collection of project reqs in the following forms.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"As headers amongst low-level requirements for organisational purposes.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"As MFs sometimes.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"When would you want to treat MFs differently to FEs? Or vica-versa.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"FEs would be too detailed and thus inappropriate for the following:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"*Comprehend what the project will do/provide.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"*Communicate the intended direction of the project (roadmap).\"}],[{\"lit\":\"*Plan versions. (eg. MF-1,2,3 in v1.0, MF-7 in v1.1, etc.)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Find missing requirements by analysing feature/scope intersections.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"MFs and FEs both could be used for:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Break work down into smaller units.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Organise low-level requirements.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"To be honest, it's like this: in most cases, for everything with a \"},{\"mono\":\"*\"},{\"lit\":\", at first one would only want to see MFs but there are times/cases where one would want more information and would benefit from being able to see a breakdown of FEs.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"If MFs & FEs were all stored together, how would that affect your usage?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Often I would only want to see top-level FEs because logically they would be MFs. I'd want to hide the detail of FEs. I'd probably store FEs under a different reqtype or not at all. Maybe I'd use groupings instead.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why are MFs normally stored separately from FEs?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Because MFs encompass many smaller parts. Usually MFs correspond with users' perceptions of functionality, where are FEs don't. For most of the business planning, FEs are not even considered because MFs are the starting points and at the right level of detail as the level of planning.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is the relationship MFs have with other requirements? What do you need to do in that sense?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Nearly all low-level requirements (90%+) are driven by MFs. Consequentially, MFs are used to filter low-level requirements, and for that to happen, of course, the LL reqs need to be attributed to MFs. It's also important for traceability.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"LL-reqs can be strongly or weakly associated to multiple MFs. Example: MF-A is strongly related because MF-A cannot exist without the req. MF-B is weakly related because if MF-B is implemented, then MF-A needs to cater for it via this requirement, however MF-B can exist without it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Because I usually use MFs to scope what I'm working on, I often want to filter my view of requirements by the associated MF. I usually just use the strongly related MF to filter what I'm interested in (whitelist). I'm often working on a few MFs at once. It would be nice to also see weakly related reqs of MFs I'm currently working on, I guess.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"MFs are also used for progress tracking. Eg. For MF-03, reqs are in 'approved' status, prototype is in 'review' status, etc.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"MF & groupings \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":7}},{\"lit\":\": ?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"MF & sem-ids \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":12}},{\"lit\":\": ?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"MF & req relationships \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":13}},{\"lit\":\": ?\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":492,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-02T11:00:47.542247Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":91},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":88},{\"gr\":13}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
