    "{\"#\":504,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:29:33.602759Z\",\"event\":{\"FieldCustomTagUpdate:2\":{\"id\":7,\"values\":[{\"reqTypes\":{\"otherwise\":\"mandatory\",\"perReqType\":{\"10\":{\"defaultTo\":13},\"3\":\"notApplicable\"}}}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":505,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:29:52.685606Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":92},\"patch\":{\"+\":[],\"-\":[13]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":506,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:30:35.899674Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":93},\"value\":[{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"View a project as it was at a previous point in time.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Tag a point in time.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"See list of changes.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Compare. See the difference between two points in time.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Scope should be the entire project, so: requirements, groupings, fields, config.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Exceptions: tags.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Tags should be modifiable, deletable. One should be able to create a tag for a previous point in time, not just the current time.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Changes are immutable. If changes are to include comments then they will need to be mutable but I don't think it's worth it; more work to dev and maintain, process becomes tedious for user.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Granularity of a change. Easiest would be atomic, eg. “User A changed UC-3 step 3.0.5.a from X to Y at T”. When viewing a list of changes, that would get tedious as users often edit the same req many times in succession. There is value in each change being recorded (rather than aggregating & saving) because one can quickly and easily delete valuable data without realising. Instead view-based tactics should probably be employed, such as wrapping up sequential changes to the same req in the list display with maybe the number of collapsed changes and a button to expand and see them all. What about bulk operations, like applying a grouping to 50 reqs, or field-set editing where all changes will probably be applied on save? Maybe that strategy being inconsistent with the reqs (presuming auto-save) is the problem; if there's auto-save for reqs there should probably be auto-save for everything including project cfg. Then undo and/or revert becomes very important.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Comparison. I imagine specifying two points in time (one defaulting to now) and seeing a list of changes between the two. Not the list of changes in between those points in time, no, just what is totally different once all changes are squashed. (eg. don't show me 20 changes to FR-4, just show me 0 or 1.)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Another idea is viewing side by side with changes highlighted. Honestly though, these are solution ideas, tool ideas. The use cases and motivations for using any of these should be analysed and I'm not doing that now.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Another thing, usage columns may need to show two values: currently-in-use, historically-in-use. Reason being that it may be confusing to see usage 0 but only be able to soft-delete instead of hard-delete.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":507,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:30:43.073751Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":94,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":508,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:31:05.614575Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":94,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Undo & Auto-Save: prelim\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":509,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:31:13.238539Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":94},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":17}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":510,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:32:34.902221Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":94},\"value\":[{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Changes to projects need to be persisted.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Multiple users can view a project simultaneously.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Multiple users can edit a project simultaneously.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"When editing, a user needs to revert & abort the change (avoiding a save and audit-trail update).\"}],[{\"lit\":\"After editing, a user needs to revert 1 or more immediate changes.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Must minimise user need to resolve conflicting concurrent changes.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Foreseeable issues:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Manual save:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" annoying UX burden, data-loss risk, may cause change-set mindfulness & strategising in idiots like me.\"}],[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Auto save per change:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" more network connectivity (degrade perf & UX), more server-side effort, more DB space, change logs too detailed (created step, indented step, edited step x10).\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Idea: If timed saves gets the go-ahead, should probably prevent data from being saved for 30 sec to avoid noisy mistakes. So if user edits field A, 30 save timer starts, then 29 sec later user edits B. 1 sec later and the 30 sec timer is up, field B shouldn't be saved because it is only 1 second old. Consider this a min-bound; similarly, a max bound would be desirable. If for what ever reason a person spends 20min on the same req then something goes wrong, you losing the entire 20min of work would be unacceptable. It should probably not wait longer than 3min or so.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Going to think about some phase-2-relevant concerns.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Data loss must be avoided at all costs. Doing it for grouping types, fields etc. Req content must've be losable. Minimum required = save history, don't even need to make it accessible at first.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Immediately mistakes are not uncommon. Hence immediate undo is required.\"}]]},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Moving notes out of plan.md:\"}]},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Undo an undo.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Connection problems.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Validation problems. (Eg. cyclic structs, etc.) Delayed saving probably fine but validation is better asap.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Knock-on effects such as add/del/reind step handled how? Am I conflating saving + history concerns with multi-user anti-conflict concerns? Seems like it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Actually \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":17}},{\"lit\":\" shouldn't be a problem until there are multiple users (in a single-user ctx it only affects multiple tabs). Maybe simplest would be best until phase 3? Consider history reqs for data structures but whack save buttons on things and/or auto-save (LL-reqs) where appropriate for now. UX inconsistency but maybe ok short-term, changability cost shouldn't be high.\"}]]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":511,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:32:50.906777Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":95,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":512,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:32:57.356056Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":95,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Collaboration: authoring: prelim\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":513,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:33:04.512269Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":95,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Collaboration: authoring (prelim)\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":514,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:34:35.541562Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":95},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Requirements are normally authored by BAs on a project. A project often has multiple BAs, usually on the same team. I'm sure places exist where they would want non-BAs contributing directly to requirements (without the bottleneck of going through the BA), in fact some places may want to store and track all requirements but not even have a BA; PM & devs would edit reqs themselves.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So the system needs to allow multiple users writing to the same project, sometimes even the same requirement concurrently. I also want to have multiple browser tabs open on the same computer (so same session, user, IP, MAC) and have concurrent editing without a problem.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"As with any multi-user situation permissions and security management is necessary. Here are some examples of groups/roles: PM, Head BA, BAs, project owner, stakeholder, tester, dev, “reader” (grant read-access to some randoms), business users, client, ops, designers. Plus there will be cases where different teams need to collaborate on intersection reqs, in which roles on their own may not suffice; it may become necessary to restrict access to a subset of a project. Example: I'm building a big system and component B requires collaboration with team X; I may want to grant team X read access to the entire project, edit access to reqs with grouping ComponentB, and create-req access with the constraint that reqs they create are tagged with grouping ComponentB.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Intersection with \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":6}},{\"lit\":\" here, if there are multiple authors on a project then it may become necessary to be able to assign incompletions to 0:n users and have users be able to filter out other people/team's tasks in incompletion views.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Intersection with \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":8}},{\"lit\":\", all changes will need to be attributable to a user.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"A project owner will need to be able to hand ownership over to another user.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"The scope of a project isn't governed by the laws of nature; sometimes a project splits off into smaller ones, sometimes separate projects merge into a single one. I'd say that these cases legitimately fall under the umbrella of collaboration. Actually there'd probably be a real-world need to have collaboration between projects without merging them (esp with intersections). What would be required? Maybe just references? Shared groupings? Who knows. Needs analysis. Plus it could probably safely be moved to its own MF.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"With collaboration comes conflict, mistakes, idiocy; quite likely someone good or authoritative may be unsatisfied with the contribution of other authors and may want to: undo their shit, reject a contribution with a request of amendments, ask them questions about a contribution, create a discussion around a contentious contribution, ask another user to review/confirm an amendment. Most of these could (and probably should) be pushed outside the scope of ShipReq in which case the focus shifts to anything required to facilitate the manual process. Very importantly, this leads to...\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Notifications and watching! This should probably be its own MF. I want to know of all changes that happen on a project, or that affect a subset of the requirements. I want an email for each one \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"(really?)\"}]},{\"lit\":\". I want an email every 2 hours, every week, etc. summarising all the changes that occurred in that time period. I want to be able to notify other users in the system, eg. “@golly pls confirm”.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":515,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:34:47.585996Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":95},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":9}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":516,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:34:58.841828Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":96,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":517,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:34:59.071557Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":97,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":518,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:35:18.689354Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":96,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Collaboration: stakeholders (prelim)\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":519,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:35:26.657430Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":96},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":10}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":520,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:36:27.574169Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":96},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Most of this will be similar to \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":95}},{\"lit\":\". By stakeholders I mean people who have an interest in the project but are not on the project team, so clients, sponsors, business users, group heads, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What do they need? There are two classifications here, 1) interest in the detail, 2) interest in the high-level.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"With an interest in the detail are future end-users, marketers & sales, often the client/sponsor for smaller projects of work, or in smaller organisations (esp. small businesses). They need to periodically review and approve requirements, comment on requirements to ask questions, request amendments. Similar to MF-11 you don't want them reviewing the same shit needlessly, if they approve something once and it doesn't change, they should never have to re-review it again. They should be able to filter out everything they've reviewed previously and read through only the remainder of reqs. This is I think a powerful feature. Consensus is conventionally hard and off-putting but paramount to success. I want to attack the pain points of\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Too much information.\"}]},{\"lit\":\" – don't demand the user remember what they haven't checked yet, or ask them to check the same thing twice. If a req was previously approved, modified and now needs re-approval, the system should make it super-obvious what changed (sometimes a req's text is large, a change small, and requiring the user to reread the entire requirement would be another instance of TMI).\"}],[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Traceability.\"}]},{\"lit\":\" – Protects involved parties like contracts do. People can't bullshit and say they didn't agree, or didn't see, or wasn't told.\"}],[{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Time and effort.\"}]},{\"lit\":\" – This is a massive deterrent. The review/approval process needs to be as quick and easy as possible which implies it must be as simple as possible too. Should come up with a bunch of QRs and UCs for this.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"There are surely other pain points; they should be discovered. Oh and before I forget, approval should be freely revocable; prefer to push consequences outside the system as much as possible.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"With an interest in the high-level are people concerned with the progress of the project, to assess whether the project is on forecasted track (bcos their responsibility (PM) or financial (client/sponsor)), to assess where contributions are coming from, to assess what's holding the project up, to understand why progress has stalled. In these cases they'd mostly be interested in stats, charts, summaries. They're usually time-poor and non-technical won't give a shit about how ShipReqs or how to navigate it. They'd probably want a link, maybe a list of (arbitrary) things that make sense from their perspective (“Blockers”, “Features & Progress”), then a single piece of info, maybe with the ability to go from their into more detail.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Actually there's the business stuff too. Requirement types like Major Feature, Business Objective, Success Critera, Business Risk, etc. are of interest to an entire class of users that have no interest in FRs, COs, etc.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also a manager would want to know what tasks/work in pending on people in his/her team. eg. Minion A has 120 reqs to review.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I nearly forgot! One of the most important ingredients for requirement & project success is communication and socialisation. Stakeholders, everyone involved in the project, even if transitively, should be able to\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"see what the latest requirements are.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"see what's changed since they last looked, cared, committed to memory.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"be notified what something they care about (or someone else wants them to care about) changes.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Stakeholders often lack transparency.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Another idea, as noted above stakeholders need to provide feedback on reqs in the system, will they need to record comments/feedback on reqs not in the system (yet). How do they communicate that (existing req's are fine) but there are req's missing / other concerns haven't been addressed?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Similarly to how stakeholders want to approve/reject everything in an intensional subset of reqs, and only be shown updates henceforth, BAs would have use for an only-slightly abstracted feature: creating personal checklists. Say the BA or designer is creating a UI prototype externally, they'd want to tick all items in scope as they update the prototype, have those ticks disappear (or be archived) when a req is updated. The checklist should be able to be made private or else it will clutter everyone else's view. Similarly, this is also how a head BA could enforce a {Complete, Correct, Feasible, Necessary, Prioritised, Unambiguous, Verifiable} checklist for reqs.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":521,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:37:02.076972Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":97,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Deletion (prelim)\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":522,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:43:15.451527Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":97},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"There have been some major changes that affect all requirements pertaining to deletion. Project storage is now via an append-only event-stream. As such history is never lost and can easily be made accessible to the user.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Deletion subjects:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Config\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"◦ Tags\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Issue types\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Fields\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Req types\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Content\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Generic requirements\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Req code groups\"}]]},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Tags\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a tag?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Tags are fickle things. They often imprecise. \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Target versions\"}]},{\"lit\":\" change all the time; after seeing how statuses are being used one might decide to merge some, remove some; tags representing components can be changed to cover different subsets of a solution. It's also why we need to see usage – tags that rarely get used are often potential candidates for deletion.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It means it shouldn't be used anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It should be removed from existing data. Simple enough when it's just attached to something but it's a bit more involving when it's being used in text, like “Machine \"},{\"tag\":3},{\"lit\":\" do ...”. In those cases you can't just remove it, you need to either change it to another tag that fits or reword it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What if you couldn't delete tags?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd have to rename them stupidly to avoid people using them anymore. I'd want them to display in some kind of obvious way, like big and red so that BAs could see that they are obviously wrong. In fact, maybe they could be part of the issue system, like how other types of issues are reported and easily actionable.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Maybe if it's still in use – because then it's not really deleted. And the intent of tag deletion is removal of use.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Tags are fickle things like I said. Plus sometimes there's trial and error involved. You want tags to be decently distributed; you might delete stuff, add new tags, allocate them and realise you're worse off.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd need to add the tag back (quick) and then re-tag everything (annoying).\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"tag → parent tag\\ntag → child tags\\ntag → field\\ntag → req/code-group tag-pool\\ntag → req/code-group text\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Issue Types\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete an issue type?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Like tags, it's just a fickle idea to reduce data into subsets.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It means the issue shouldn't be usable anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Those issues either need to change type, or be removed.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same as tags. Rename stupidly. Or actually, rename it the next time I want to create a new issue type.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"If it's in use still – because something needs to be done about those issues.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same as tags.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Add it back (quick). Maybe change some existing issues to use it again.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"issue type → req/code-group text\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Fields\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a field?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd delete a field if it wasn't really being used in practice.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I'd delete a tag field if I deleted (without replacing) the underlying tag.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I'd delete an implication field if I changed the req-types, say if I merged two req types into one and they both had fields. Actually if I deleted the underlying req type for any reason, I'd need to get rid of its field. Although that should probably be automatic right?\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"That fields is gone. Can't add new data to it, can't see it anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Hmm, I guess I'd probably still want to be able to see it if I need to. Like if it's a text field, if I deleted the field I probably wouldn't move that field data around. I'd just leave it but one day I might need to read it again and extract anything useful.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete a field?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Nothing I guess. But I'd want to rename the field at least to indicate not to add any new data to it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Well I just wouldn't want to lose data. If it deleted the field and the data with it, that would be bad. Gathered BA data (usually from interviews and analysis) should never be lost.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"New requirements might come in that revalidate the existence of the field, so I'd wanna get it back again and populate new rows with it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Or someone with different needs might say they really need it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind after a field was deleted.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd want to add it back again and not lose any data.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"field ←req type (implication)\\nfield ←tag\\nfield ←req types (applicability)\\nfield → req field values\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Req Types\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a req type?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It might not be getting used. Or we might just look at our data differently and decide we have a better way of representing it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It means we shouldn't have any reqs allocated to it anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"They should be reallocated to a different req type. Or rarely, just deleted.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete a req type?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Rename it like my answers to the other questions.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"We might have printed a report, or stored references to our reqs in other systems. In both cases the external entity will have an ID to a req that contains the req type. If we deleted the req type, it would break their references. They should always be able to use those references to look up the same reqs. If a req type is deleted, reqs should still remember their old req types & IDs. We should still be able to delete req types though.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same reason for why I would delete one.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd want to add the req type back, maybe change reqs back to use it again.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"req type → field (implication)\\nreq type → field (applicability)\\nreq type → pubid register\\nreq type → associated generic reqs\\nreq type → refs in text\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Generic Requirements\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a req?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"An underlying (implying) requirement could change.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Or people's minds could change, or new information is discovered. Then existing requirements become obsolete and need to be deleted.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Turned off. Not visible anymore unless someone wants to search or look through stuff that's been removed.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Refs to it (from non-deleted stuff) should probably be considered errors. Not just text refs, but implications too. In that nothing alive should be implied by something dead. Wait, unless it's implied by something else in which case just ignore the dead implication.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Tag them as deleted.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Dunno.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same reason you might delete one. Things change, life changes.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd probably just want to undo it. All it's old implications should be restored. It's req codes and their groups should come back. Text refs to it should be fine again (i.e. not an error anymore).\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What if the req codes are in use now?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I guess the ones being undeleted should be renamed. they should still form the same trees though – I wouldn't want one renamed but not others. Why? Cos I'd need to manually take care of the conflict and for that I'd want to look at what exists now and then the entire undeleted tree with its structure as it was.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"gen req ← refs in text\\ngen req ↔ gen reqs (implication)\\ngen req ↔ req codes associated\\ngen req -- req code groups (indirectly)\\ngen req → req data (fields, tags, text)\\ngen req ← pubid register\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Req Code Groups\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete an RCG?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"If I reorganise my reqs and it becomes obsolete.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If I delete a bunch of reqs and the code group is only useful in that group of reqs.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"I don't need it anymore. I don't want to see it anymore.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I want it removed with the reqs being removed.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Refs to it need to be removed. Children are fine if they still exist.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete groups?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd rename them, eventually recycle them and hate you.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Nope.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Reorg, becomes relevant again.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I undelete a group of reqs that came under the group.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Recreate it. Think of and re-enter a meaningful title again. Would be nice if I didn't have to do this.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Recreate all the req code groups I used to have. I'd have to remember titles or think of new ones. All of that would be annoying. Ideally they'd all just come back with the req undeletion.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"rcg → req code children\\nrcg → text refs\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Finally...\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Also we should be able to record a reason for deletion. For example I might select 10 things, delete them all at once and give the reason “FR-201 makes this redundant” or something.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Because it's not always going to be obvious why something is deleted. You might search for something, find it dead and not be able to think of a reason why it shouldn't be alive, then you could undelete it without understanding that it's incompatible with another requirement.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if the system didn't support this?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I guess I'd edit requirements before I delete them so include the reason. But that would be super annoying when deleting an entire block of reqs.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":523,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:44:07.172208Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":97},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"There have been some major changes that affect all requirements pertaining to deletion. Project storage is now via an append-only event-stream. As such history is never lost and can easily be made accessible to the user.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Deletion subjects:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Config\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"◦ Tags\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Issue types\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Fields\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Req types\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Content\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Generic requirements\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"* Req code groups\"}]]},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Tags\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a tag?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Tags are fickle things. They often imprecise. \"},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Target versions\"}]},{\"lit\":\" change all the time; after seeing how statuses are being used one might decide to merge some, remove some; tags representing components can be changed to cover different subsets of a solution. It's also why we need to see usage – tags that rarely get used are often potential candidates for deletion.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It means it shouldn't be used anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It should be removed from existing data. Simple enough when it's just attached to something but it's a bit more involving when it's being used in text, like “Machine \"},{\"tag\":3},{\"lit\":\" do ...”. In those cases you can't just remove it, you need to either change it to another tag that fits or reword it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What if you couldn't delete tags?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd have to rename them stupidly to avoid people using them anymore. I'd want them to display in some kind of obvious way, like big and red so that BAs could see that they are obviously wrong. In fact, maybe they could be part of the issue system, like how other types of issues are reported and easily actionable.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Maybe if it's still in use – because then it's not really deleted. And the intent of tag deletion is removal of use.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Tags are fickle things like I said. Plus sometimes there's trial and error involved. You want tags to be decently distributed; you might delete stuff, add new tags, allocate them and realise you're worse off.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd need to add the tag back (quick) and then re-tag everything (annoying).\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"tag → parent tag\\ntag → child tags\\ntag → field\\ntag → req/code-group tag-pool\\ntag → req/code-group text\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Issue Types\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete an issue type?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Like tags, it's just a fickle idea to reduce data into subsets.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It means the issue shouldn't be usable anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Those issues either need to change type, or be removed.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same as tags. Rename stupidly. Or actually, rename it the next time I want to create a new issue type.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"If it's in use still – because something needs to be done about those issues.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same as tags.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Add it back (quick). Maybe change some existing issues to use it again.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"issue type → req/code-group text\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Fields\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a field?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd delete a field if it wasn't really being used in practice.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I'd delete a tag field if I deleted (without replacing) the underlying tag.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I'd delete an implication field if I changed the req-types, say if I merged two req types into one and they both had fields. Actually if I deleted the underlying req type for any reason, I'd need to get rid of its field. Although that should probably be automatic right?\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"That fields is gone. Can't add new data to it, can't see it anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Hmm, I guess I'd probably still want to be able to see it if I need to. Like if it's a text field, if I deleted the field I probably wouldn't move that field data around. I'd just leave it but one day I might need to read it again and extract anything useful.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete a field?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Nothing I guess. But I'd want to rename the field at least to indicate not to add any new data to it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Well I just wouldn't want to lose data. If it deleted the field and the data with it, that would be bad. Gathered BA data (usually from interviews and analysis) should never be lost.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"New requirements might come in that revalidate the existence of the field, so I'd wanna get it back again and populate new rows with it.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Or someone with different needs might say they really need it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind after a field was deleted.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd want to add it back again and not lose any data.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"field ← req type (implication)\\nfield ← tag\\nfield ← req types (applicability)\\nfield → req field values\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Req Types\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a req type?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It might not be getting used. Or we might just look at our data differently and decide we have a better way of representing it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It means we shouldn't have any reqs allocated to it anymore.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"They should be reallocated to a different req type. Or rarely, just deleted.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete a req type?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Rename it like my answers to the other questions.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"We might have printed a report, or stored references to our reqs in other systems. In both cases the external entity will have an ID to a req that contains the req type. If we deleted the req type, it would break their references. They should always be able to use those references to look up the same reqs. If a req type is deleted, reqs should still remember their old req types & IDs. We should still be able to delete req types though.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same reason for why I would delete one.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd want to add the req type back, maybe change reqs back to use it again.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"req type → field (implication)\\nreq type → field (applicability)\\nreq type → pubid register\\nreq type → associated generic reqs\\nreq type → refs in text\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Generic Requirements\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete a req?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"An underlying (implying) requirement could change.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Or people's minds could change, or new information is discovered. Then existing requirements become obsolete and need to be deleted.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Turned off. Not visible anymore unless someone wants to search or look through stuff that's been removed.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Refs to it (from non-deleted stuff) should probably be considered errors. Not just text refs, but implications too. In that nothing alive should be implied by something dead. Wait, unless it's implied by something else in which case just ignore the dead implication.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Tag them as deleted.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Dunno.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Same reason you might delete one. Things change, life changes.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd probably just want to undo it. All it's old implications should be restored. It's req codes and their groups should come back. Text refs to it should be fine again (i.e. not an error anymore).\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What if the req codes are in use now?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I guess the ones being undeleted should be renamed. they should still form the same trees though – I wouldn't want one renamed but not others. Why? Cos I'd need to manually take care of the conflict and for that I'd want to look at what exists now and then the entire undeleted tree with its structure as it was.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"gen req ← refs in text\\ngen req ↔ gen reqs (implication)\\ngen req ↔ req codes associated\\ngen req - req code groups (indirectly)\\ngen req → req data (fields, tags, text)\\ngen req ← pubid register\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Req Code Groups\"}]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why would you delete an RCG?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"If I reorganise my reqs and it becomes obsolete.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If I delete a bunch of reqs and the code group is only useful in that group of reqs.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does it mean to be deleted? Can you explain without using the word delete?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"I don't need it anymore. I don't want to see it anymore.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I want it removed with the reqs being removed.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What does that mean for existing data?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Refs to it need to be removed. Children are fine if they still exist.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if you couldn't delete groups?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'd rename them, eventually recycle them and hate you.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any cases where deletion shouldn't be allowed? If so, why? What if it happens anyway?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Nope.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What is a reason you would change your mind about a deletion?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Reorg, becomes relevant again.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I undelete a group of reqs that came under the group.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you need to do if you changed your mind about a deletion.\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Recreate it. Think of and re-enter a meaningful title again. Would be nice if I didn't have to do this.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Recreate all the req code groups I used to have. I'd have to remember titles or think of new ones. All of that would be annoying. Ideally they'd all just come back with the req undeletion.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Data relationships:\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"rcg → req code children\\nrcg → text refs\"}},{\"h1\":[{\"lit\":\"Finally...\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Also we should be able to record a reason for deletion. For example I might select 10 things, delete them all at once and give the reason “FR-201 makes this redundant” or something.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Because it's not always going to be obvious why something is deleted. You might search for something, find it dead and not be able to think of a reason why it shouldn't be alive, then you could undelete it without understanding that it's incompatible with another requirement.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What would you do if the system didn't support this?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I guess I'd edit requirements before I delete them so include the reason. But that would be super annoying when deleting an entire block of reqs.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":524,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:44:39.034844Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":98,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":525,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:44:47.147097Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":98},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"ShipReq as it stands is currently only useful for 1-person projects. Two people can't work together unless they share the same login, which is terrible for everyone including me. It's critical that I add multi user support.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I need a team to be able to use ShipReq collaboratively. It can be really simple at first: just allow the project owner to add/remove users to a collaborators list. Once on the list, a collaborator will see the project in their projects list and be able to work on it just like the owner. Simple.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Another expansion of the simplicity would be to allow the transference of ownership. I don't know if that means the new owner would need to accept ownership first but whatever, it's more about enabling capability at this point to get the business running. Plenty of time for goldplating and improvement once I've got real users, I mean features that won't be used until I've got a good bunch of users needn't be built now. Btw, Whatsapp has a simple model wrt to group chats. One or more admins, transfer as much as you like. Leave and ownership transfers to a random collaborator. Simple & easy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So once multiple users can work on a project together it then introduces a bunch of new requirements. Maybe these should be separate but still, here are the thoughts:\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If I'm working on a project with someone, I'm going to want to know what changes they're making. Potential solutions are:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"audit trail\"}],[{\"lit\":\"diff of project between T₁ (eg. when I last logged in), and T₂ (eg. now) – I mean actual diff, not list of events\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Also want to communicate with other collaborators. Potential ideas: inline chat, tag them in places to leave them inline msgs. Maybe have columns (fields) with user(s) as values to represent assignees; in which case will probably want to have a many-to-many acyclic tree like tags so that user groups can exist and fields can be constrained by upper bounds (eg. assigned testers vs devs vs clients). Whatever the combination of solutions, when I login I want to be able to quickly see <whatever>: if I have any unread chat msgs, if I've been recently tagged, where and why I'm still tagged, what shit I've been assigned, etc. I want it to be quick and easy. If I have to go to ReqTable and write my own filters then that's not quick and easy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Will definitely need new filter capabilities. Example:{createdBy,updatedBy,containsRefTo} {me,@blah}\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"An interesting side-effect of multiusernessness is that it introduces the consideration of personal vs global data/config. The one example is saved views.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Users should be able to create their own saved views\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Users shouldn't have to see everyone else's\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Users (eg admin) should be able to create saved views for the team\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What else is there apart from saved views?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Most of the thought above considers multiple authors. Not all users are req authors though. Other user classes that jump out are:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"devs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"testers\"}],[{\"lit\":\"clients / product owner\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Full detail here is probably going to far; there's no need to plan the entire roadmap right now. Some quick high-level thoughts now, detail later...\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"devs & testers – want to know what's assigned to them, see what version, and modify the status & assignee\"}],[{\"lit\":\"devs, maybe testers, maybe clients – probably want notifications when certain reqs change\"}],[{\"lit\":\"clients – want to know the overall/high-level status, eg. how is MF-1 progressing, how much is done, pending, what releases will it go in to\"}],[{\"lit\":\"everyone – for scope X, who made certain changes (i.e. if a req changes and even everyone gets notifications, great, but also need to know who made changes so they can talk to them if problem)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"everyone – suggest/demand changes but not make it themselves\"}],[{\"lit\":\"everyone – ask questions about a req?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Now let's talk about audit trails. Users need to be able to see them, they'll be long so also filter and scroll around. Users need to be able to view the entire project audit trail, but it's also important the each req display the relevant events in ReqDetail. What I mean by that is if you open up a req in ReqDetail, down the bottom there should be a read-only field that shows a subset of the global audit trail that are events that have impacted the selected req (like the history tab in jira). It might be annoying to always display the list because it could be very long and distracting, maybe the field could have a little button saying “show” or something?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It also might be a common case to want to see all changes made by other users since the current user's last change.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So looking at a big list is going to be useful sometimes but other times it's going to be useless because there's too much repetitive (and intermediate) information. In such cases a user needs the ability to see a diff between revisions. The user should be able to choose the start/end revs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also, once we have read-only mode available, user should be able to view the project at an old revision.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Baselining is a common thing is requirements. Our audit trail means we're a bit like git for requirements. We can tag revisions and see changes since, etc. I'm not sure if users should be allowed to modify revision tags, probably – ShipReq isn't a preventative product. Probably there should be permissioning at the project level and maybe even the tag level to declare who can and can't modify tags once they're created. Notifications are out of scope right now but maybe in future all relevant parties will be notified when a tag is modified. In fact, tagging should be part of the audit trail (unlike Git).\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Treating ShipReq like git leads to an obvious question: do we allow branching? DEFINATELY not in the medium term, I've got no fucking customers. But in future... maybe? An idea is that requirement existence (i.e. IDs) exist globally, but are included in some branches. This means that merging a branch doesn't result in multiple reqs fighting for the same ids, and it also captures an interesting aspect of the reality in that when you focus on a branch, the other stuff still exists in reality, it's just not part of the branch you're looking at. But merge conflicts would be inevitable. Don't want to have to think about that right now.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":526,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:46:29.508720Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":98},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"ShipReq as it stands is currently only useful for 1-person projects. Two people can't work together unless they share the same login, which is terrible for everyone including me. It's critical that I add multi user support.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I need a team to be able to use ShipReq collaboratively. It can be really simple at first: just allow the project owner to add/remove users to a collaborators list. Once on the list, a collaborator will see the project in their projects list and be able to work on it just like the owner. Simple.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Another expansion of the simplicity would be to allow the transference of ownership. I don't know if that means the new owner would need to accept ownership first but whatever, it's more about enabling capability at this point to get the business running. Plenty of time for goldplating and improvement once I've got real users, I mean features that won't be used until I've got a good bunch of users needn't be built now. Btw, Whatsapp has a simple model wrt to group chats. One or more admins, transfer as much as you like. Leave and ownership transfers to a random collaborator. Simple & easy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So once multiple users can work on a project together it then introduces a bunch of new requirements. Maybe these should be separate but still, here are the thoughts:\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"If I'm working on a project with someone, I'm going to want to know what changes they're making. Potential solutions are:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"audit trail\"}],[{\"lit\":\"diff of project between T₁ (eg. when I last logged in), and T₂ (eg. now) – I mean actual diff, not list of events\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Also want to communicate with other collaborators. Potential ideas: inline chat, tag them in places to leave them inline msgs. Maybe have columns (fields) with user(s) as values to represent assignees; in which case will probably want to have a many-to-many acyclic tree like tags so that user groups can exist and fields can be constrained by upper bounds (eg. assigned testers vs devs vs clients). Whatever the combination of solutions, when I login I want to be able to quickly see <whatever>: if I have any unread chat msgs, if I've been recently tagged, where and why I'm still tagged, what shit I've been assigned, etc. I want it to be quick and easy. If I have to go to ReqTable and write my own filters then that's not quick and easy.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Will definitely need new filter capabilities. Example:{createdBy,updatedBy,containsRefTo} {me,@blah}\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"An interesting side-effect of multiusernessness is that it introduces the consideration of personal vs global data/config. The one example is saved views.\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Users should be able to create their own saved views\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Users shouldn't have to see everyone else's\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Users (eg admin) should be able to create saved views for the team\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"What else is there apart from saved views?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Most of the thought above considers multiple \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"authors\"}]},{\"lit\":\". Not all users are req authors though. Other user classes that jump out are:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"devs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"testers\"}],[{\"lit\":\"clients / product owner\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Full detail here is probably going to far; there's no need to plan the entire roadmap right now. Some quick high-level thoughts now, detail later...\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"devs & testers – want to know what's assigned to them, see what version, and modify the status & assignee\"}],[{\"lit\":\"devs, maybe testers, maybe clients – probably want notifications when certain reqs change\"}],[{\"lit\":\"clients – want to know the overall/high-level status, eg. how is MF-1 progressing, how much is done, pending, what releases will it go in to\"}],[{\"lit\":\"everyone – for scope X, who made certain changes (i.e. if a req changes and even everyone gets notifications, great, but also need to know who made changes so they can talk to them if problem)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"everyone – suggest/demand changes but not make it themselves\"}],[{\"lit\":\"everyone – ask questions about a req?\"}]]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":527,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:46:53.472409Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":98,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Collaboration: authoring (prelim2)\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":528,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:47:05.191004Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":98},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":95}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":529,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:47:22.054439Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":98},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":9}],\"-\":[{\"gr\":95}]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":530,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:47:30.183052Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":99,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":531,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:47:41.194306Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":99,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"History/Audit (prelim2)\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":532,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-03T01:48:01.243576Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":99},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Now let's talk about audit trails. Users need to be able to see them, they'll be long so also filter and scroll around. Users need to be able to view the entire project audit trail, but it's also important the each req display the relevant events in ReqDetail. What I mean by that is if you open up a req in ReqDetail, down the bottom there should be a read-only field that shows a subset of the global audit trail that are events that have impacted the selected req (like the history tab in jira). It might be annoying to always display the list because it could be very long and distracting, maybe the field could have a little button saying “show” or something?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It also might be a common case to want to see all changes made by other users since the current user's last change.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So looking at a big list is going to be useful sometimes but other times it's going to be useless because there's too much repetitive (and intermediate) information. In such cases a user needs the ability to see a diff between revisions. The user should be able to choose the start/end revs.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Also, once we have read-only mode available, user should be able to view the project at an old revision.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Baselining is a common thing is requirements. Our audit trail means we're a bit like git for requirements. We can tag revisions and see changes since, etc. I'm not sure if users should be allowed to modify revision tags, probably – ShipReq isn't a preventative product. Probably there should be permissioning at the project level and maybe even the tag level to declare who can and can't modify tags once they're created. Notifications are out of scope right now but maybe in future all relevant parties will be notified when a tag is modified. In fact, tagging should be part of the audit trail (unlike Git).\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Treating ShipReq like git leads to an obvious question: do we allow branching? DEFINATELY not in the medium term, I've got no fucking customers. But in future... maybe? An idea is that requirement existence (i.e. IDs) exist globally, but are included in some branches. This means that merging a branch doesn't result in multiple reqs fighting for the same ids, and it also captures an interesting aspect of the reality in that when you focus on a branch, the other stuff still exists in reality, it's just not part of the branch you're looking at. But merge conflicts would be inevitable. Don't want to have to think about that right now.\"}]}}}",
