    "{\"#\":573,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-10T02:44:08.156723Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":102},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Deepti was entering requirements following Chen's process where you do interviews first, then create MFs after analysing them. In that case you have IV → MF but her IV's MF field was blank (and showing as an issue) because imp field calculation only considers backwards-implication, not forwards. Thinking about this it seems to make sense that forward-implication be considered too. The reason I'm not just gonna jump in and implement it is that I'm concerned about transitivity. Should it be transitive? Seems like it definitely should, but then what about large, complex trees? Will there be problems? Needs analysis.... And here we are.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Will there be problems with transitive forward implication?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Let's just consider some scenarios:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"IV-1 → MF-1:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" IV-1 should definitely have MF-1 as in it's MF field\"}],[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"IV-1 → IV-2 → MF-1:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" As above, IV-2 should definitely have MF-1 as in it's MF field, it seems logical that IV-1 should too. eg. \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"\\\"we need to solve X\\\"\"}]},{\"lit\":\" → \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"\\\"here's how we can solve X, with MF-1!\\\"\"}]},{\"lit\":\" → MF-1\"}],[{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"FB1 --> IV1 --> UC1 --> IV2\"}},{\"lit\":\"and then\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"MF4\\n ↓\\nFB3 ---------------------------------------------------+\\n ↑                                                     |\\nFB4                                                    |\\n                                                       |\\nFB2 -------------------------------------------+       |\\n                                               ↓       ↓\\nFB1 --> IV1 --> UC1(DEAD) --> IV2 --> UC2 --> MF1 --> FR1\\n         |                     ↑       |\\n         +---------------------+       +----> MF2 --> MF3\\n           (manually relinked)\"}},{\"lit\":\"With transitive forward-implication being considered we end up with\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"    FB1 - MF1,2\\n    FB2 - MF1\\n    FB3 - MF4. INTERESTING!! should be MF1 also be included because FR-1's MF is MF1?\\n    FB4 - ∅.   INTERESTING!! should inherit FB3's MF field values\\n    IV1 - MF1,2\\n    IV2 - MF1,2\\n    UC2 - MF1,2\\n    MF1 - should be off but if not, should only be self.  DANGEROUS if MF-2 were included because UC2→MF1, and UC2 has MF1,2 in it's MF field\\n    MF2 - should be off but if not, should only be self.  DANGEROUS if MF-1 were included because UC2→MF2, and UC2 has MF1,2 in it's MF field\\n    MF3 - should be off but if not, should be self + MF2. DANGEROUS as above, shouldn't include MF1\\n    MF4 - should be off but if not, should only be self.  DANGEROUS if MF-1 were included because of FR1\"}}]]},{\"lit\":\"Shit, so that's interesting.\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"transitive forward implication seems to be ok\"}],[{\"lit\":\"it doesn't seem to be enough in the case of FB3→FR1.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Problems\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"the FB{3,4} cases should consider values in the MF field of forward imps\"}],[{\"lit\":\"if MF1 → MF2 then it can't be a cycle\"}],[{\"lit\":\"MF1 shouldn't consider UC2's MF field (because it's backwards? or because subject is also MF?)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"should this be implemented universally or should there be some config in the imp field?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"how will this affect the imp graph? everything relevant should be visible - i.e. if we're looking at FB3, it will show FR1, but it should also show MF1 (not UC2 though)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"the whole fucking thing about implication is that \"},{\"mono\":\"(A ⇒ B) ≠> (B ⇒ A)\"},{\"lit\":\" - FB3 implied FR1, maybe FR1 can exist without FB3. Why should FB3 inherit it's MF?\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What's the precise new rule?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Let's do it step by step...\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Firstly, what's the expectation?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Well it was quite hard to think about this in a vacuum so I sat down with Deepti and her dad to go through it. What really, really helped was giving some reqs some realistic meanings as follows:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"MF1 - Allow users to upload document\"}],[{\"lit\":\"MF4 - Provide users with self-hosted email accounts\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FR1 - Users must login\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FB3 - Requirements from security guys' about logging in\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FB4 - Requirements from security guys' about logging in\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"This makes it much easier to see that FB3 and FB4 should be associated with MF1 and MF4.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It also (finally) provides an conceptual intuition for why the current implication field calculation is good, but doesn't go far enough. Basically an MF forms an umbrella that houses all of its subtasks (i.e. forwards-facing implication tree). What we're missing is that any reqs \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"outside\"}]},{\"lit\":\" of that umbrella that imply something \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"in\"}]},{\"lit\":\" the umbrella, need to also be in scope (i.e. be associated with the MF). The exception is external MFs that imply reqs in scope, are to be excluded and no traversed for further implications. \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"It makes so much sense and I'm so happy this has been discovered.\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"FB1 - 1,2,3\\nFB2 - 1\\nFB3 - 1,4\\nFB4 - 1,4\\nIV1 - 1,2,3\\nIV2 - 1,2,3\\nUC2 - 1,2,3\\nMF1 - 1\\nMF2 - 2\\nMF3 - 2,3\\nMF4 - 4\"}},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[{\"lit\":\"below is old and probably invalid\"}],\"type\":1}},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"all MFs in the subject's backward & forward implication tree\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"FB1 - 1,2\\nFB2 - 1\\nFB3 - 4\\nFB4 - ∅\\nIV1 - 1,2\\nIV2 - 1,2\\nUC2 - 1,2\\nMF1 - 1\\nMF2 - 2,3   ERROR: cycle\\nMF3 - 2,3   ERROR: cycle\\nMF4 - 4\"}}]]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":574,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-13T00:05:05.487516Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":102},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Deepti was entering requirements following Chen's process where you do interviews first, then create MFs after analysing them. In that case you have IV → MF but her IV's MF field was blank (and showing as an issue) because imp field calculation only considers backwards-implication, not forwards. Thinking about this it seems to make sense that forward-implication be considered too. The reason I'm not just gonna jump in and implement it is that I'm concerned about transitivity. Should it be transitive? Seems like it definitely should, but then what about large, complex trees? Will there be problems? Needs analysis.... And here we are.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Will there be problems with transitive forward implication?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Let's just consider some scenarios:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"IV-1 → MF-1:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" IV-1 should definitely have MF-1 as in it's MF field\"}],[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"IV-1 → IV-2 → MF-1:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" As above, IV-2 should definitely have MF-1 as in it's MF field, it seems logical that IV-1 should too. eg. \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"\\\"we need to solve X\\\"\"}]},{\"lit\":\" → \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"\\\"here's how we can solve X, with MF-1!\\\"\"}]},{\"lit\":\" → MF-1\"}],[{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"FB1 --> IV1 --> UC1 --> IV2\"}},{\"lit\":\"and then\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"MF4\\n ↓\\nFB3 ---------------------------------------------------+\\n ↑                                                     |\\nFB4                                                    |\\n                                                       |\\nFB2 -------------------------------------------+       |\\n                                               ↓       ↓\\nFB1 --> IV1 --> UC1(DEAD) --> IV2 --> UC2 --> MF1 --> FR1\\n         |                     ↑       |\\n         +---------------------+       +----> MF2 --> MF3\\n           (manually relinked)\"}},{\"lit\":\"With transitive forward-implication being considered we end up with\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"    FB1 - MF1,2\\n    FB2 - MF1\\n    FB3 - MF4. INTERESTING!! should be MF1 also be included because FR-1's MF is MF1?\\n    FB4 - ∅.   INTERESTING!! should inherit FB3's MF field values\\n    IV1 - MF1,2\\n    IV2 - MF1,2\\n    UC2 - MF1,2\\n    MF1 - should be off but if not, should only be self.  DANGEROUS if MF-2 were included because UC2→MF1, and UC2 has MF1,2 in it's MF field\\n    MF2 - should be off but if not, should only be self.  DANGEROUS if MF-1 were included because UC2→MF2, and UC2 has MF1,2 in it's MF field\\n    MF3 - should be off but if not, should be self + MF2. DANGEROUS as above, shouldn't include MF1\\n    MF4 - should be off but if not, should only be self.  DANGEROUS if MF-1 were included because of FR1\"}}]]},{\"lit\":\"Shit, so that's interesting.\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"transitive forward implication seems to be ok\"}],[{\"lit\":\"it doesn't seem to be enough in the case of FB3→FR1.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Problems\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"the FB{3,4} cases should consider values in the MF field of forward imps\"}],[{\"lit\":\"if MF1 → MF2 then it can't be a cycle\"}],[{\"lit\":\"MF1 shouldn't consider UC2's MF field (because it's backwards? or because subject is also MF?)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"should this be implemented universally or should there be some config in the imp field?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"how will this affect the imp graph? everything relevant should be visible - i.e. if we're looking at FB3, it will show FR1, but it should also show MF1 (not UC2 though)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"the whole fucking thing about implication is that \"},{\"mono\":\"(A ⇒ B) ≠> (B ⇒ A)\"},{\"lit\":\" - FB3 implied FR1, maybe FR1 can exist without FB3. Why should FB3 inherit it's MF?\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What's the precise new rule?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Well it was quite hard to think about this in a vacuum so I sat down with Deepti and her dad to go through it. What really, really helped was giving some reqs some realistic meanings as follows:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"MF1 - Allow users to upload document\"}],[{\"lit\":\"MF4 - Provide users with self-hosted email accounts\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FR1 - Users must login\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FB3 - Requirements from security guys' about logging in\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FB4 - Requirements from security guys' about logging in\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"This makes it much easier to see that FB3 and FB4 should be associated with MF1 and MF4.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It also (finally) provides an conceptual intuition for why the current implication field calculation is good, but doesn't go far enough. Basically an MF forms an umbrella that houses all of its subtasks (i.e. forwards-facing implication tree). What we're missing is that any reqs \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"outside\"}]},{\"lit\":\" of that umbrella that imply something \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"in\"}]},{\"lit\":\" the umbrella, need to also be in scope (i.e. be associated with the MF). The exception is external MFs that imply reqs in scope, are to be excluded and no traversed for further implications. \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"It makes so much sense and I'm so happy this has been discovered.\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"FB1 - 1,2,3\\nFB2 - 1\\nFB3 - 1,4\\nFB4 - 1,4\\nIV1 - 1,2,3\\nIV2 - 1,2,3\\nUC2 - 1,2,3\\nMF1 - 1\\nMF2 - 2\\nMF3 - 2,3\\nMF4 - 4\"}},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What else will this change affect?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"imp graph in req detail\"}]},{\"lit\":\" - all imp-field values (eg. MF) \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"must\"}]},{\"lit\":\" be present in the graph. Especially now that the rule has become more complicated, it's even more important that users understand how those values came to be there. Otherwise, there would end up being cases where users are confused as to why a value is in their imp field, so much so that they may think they're looking at a bug.\"}],[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"imp trees in req table\"}]},{\"lit\":\" (\"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":44}},{\"lit\":\") - this hasn't been analysed yet so I'll consider it later\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"I think that's it.\"}]}}}",
