Deepti and her dad to go through it. What really, really helped was giving some reqs some realistic meanings as follows:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"MF1 - Allow users to upload document\"}],[{\"lit\":\"MF4 - Provide users with self-hosted email accounts\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FR1 - Users must login\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FB3 - Requirements from security guys' about logging in\"}],[{\"lit\":\"FB4 - Requirements from security guys' about logging in\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"This makes it much easier to see that FB3 and FB4 should be associated with MF1 and MF4.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It also (finally) provides an conceptual intuition for why the current implication field calculation is good, but doesn't go far enough. Basically an MF forms an umbrella that houses all of its subtasks (i.e. forwards-facing implication tree). What we're missing is that any reqs \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"outside\"}]},{\"lit\":\" of that umbrella that imply something \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"in\"}]},{\"lit\":\" the umbrella, need to also be in scope (i.e. be associated with the MF). The exception is external MFs that imply reqs in scope, are to be excluded and no traversed for further implications. \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"It makes so much sense and I'm so happy this has been discovered.\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"FB1 - 1,2,3\\nFB2 - 1\\nFB3 - 1,4\\nFB4 - 1,4\\nIV1 - 1,2,3\\nIV2 - 1,2,3\\nUC2 - 1,2,3\\nMF1 - 1\\nMF2 - 2\\nMF3 - 2,3\\nMF4 - 4\\nFR1 - 1,4\"}},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What else will this change affect?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"imp graph in req detail\"}]},{\"lit\":\" - all imp-field values (eg. MF) \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"must\"}]},{\"lit\":\" be present in the graph. Especially now that the rule has become more complicated, it's even more important that users understand how those values came to be there. Otherwise, there would end up being cases where users are confused as to why a value is in their imp field, so much so that they may think they're looking at a bug.\"}],[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"imp trees in req table\"}]},{\"lit\":\" (\"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":44}},{\"lit\":\") - this hasn't been analysed yet so I'll consider it later\"}],[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"filter\"}]},{\"lit\":\" - need to be able to filter by an imp-field value, rather than just \"},{\"mono\":\"impliedBy:\"},{\"lit\":\" which is different logic.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"I think that's it.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Update\"}]}]},{\"lit\":\"Now that I've implemented this, the code shows that MF-2's field being 2 instead of 2,3 requires a special condition in the code.\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"it = it.filter(p.content.reqs.need(_).reqTypeId != subjectType)\",\"lang\":\"scala\"}},{\"lit\":\"If I remove that condition, the only change is that MF-2 gets values 2,3; everything else is the same. Considering this a bit more I've decided to remove the condition and update our expectations to:\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"FB1 - 1,2,3\\nFB2 - 1\\nFB3 - 1,4\\nFB4 - 1,4\\nIV1 - 1,2,3\\nIV2 - 1,2,3\\nUC2 - 1,2,3\\nMF1 - 1\\nMF2 - 2,3\\nMF3 - 2,3\\nMF4 - 4\\nFR1 - 1,4\"}},{\"lit\":\"Deepti and I discussed it and it \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"does\"}]},{\"lit\":\" make sense. Both MFs are relevant to each other and it's helpful to be shown when filtering by one or the other because it adds important, contextual information (which is a huge, core value of ShipReq). If I'm looking at MF-3 it's good to have a reminding that it's actually a subtask of a larger context.\"}]}}}",
