    "{\"#\":595,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-14T07:55:07.061474Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":106,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[{\"title\":[{\"lit\":\"GitHub integration (prelim)\"}]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":596,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-14T07:55:12.954591Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":106},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":32}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":597,\"createdAt\":\"2020-07-14T08:29:44.306110Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":106},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"ShipReq should integration with Github in order to be very helpful and appealing to developers and dev teams.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Why?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It's a pain in the ass for devs to log in to ShipReq (or JIRA or whatever) to update tasks every time they complete something. Very error prone too. Github know this and for their own issues, allow you to type in things like \\\"Fixes <ID>\\\" in commit messages in which case they will automatically closed issues on push (into \"},{\"mono\":\"master\"},{\"lit\":\"). In our case, instead of \\\"closing\\\" issues, certain verbs will add and/or remove certain tags from reqs. This will become insanely powerful, and insanely beneficial to users, when combined with \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" as it will allow devs to update entire ecosystems of reqs from single tag changes on commits. The fact that these features don't exist at the moment make it very hard for me to keep my requirements' statuses up-to-date, which prevents me from understanding what is and isn't complete and where I'm up to.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"How do you see it being used?\"}]},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"I've already mentioned modifying reqs' status via git commit messages.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"The second thing that comes to mind is simply references. Anytime a req is mentioned in a commit message (in a special format maybe?), that commit and its details should then be shown in a field in ReqDetail. I'm not sure exactly what details. One that might be super useful would be if ShipReq always showed you what branches the commits were currently in. That way it'd be really easy to see if they'd been merged (or even released if tags included as well as just branches). Holy shit, that would be awesome actually. Back on Harold, the testers (and admin) would never know what was released to prod, what was in UAT, etc. Killer!!!\"}],[{\"lit\":\"An idea that just came to mind is scanning code itself. I wonder if that would be useful? Sounds pretty computationally heavy though, so given that it's an idea I'm unsure has value, it should be very low priority.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Ideally the integration would go in the other direction as well, and turn references in commits on Github into links back to the reqs in ShipReq.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"An idea from the JIRA integration repo: we should also convert refs in Github issue text to links to ShipReq.\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Maybe there are other cool and useful things but there is a burning need for first two points above and I think the focus should be just on those two points, and then anything else can come later with much, much less urgency.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Other\"}]},{\"lit\":\"This feature should really be just \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"\\\"Git integration\\\"\"}]},{\"lit\":\" rather than just Github. Gitlab is the 2nd most popular and should be supported next. To that end, there should be a bunch of service-agnostic endpoints on ShipReq that any service can talk to. Hell, it should even be publicly-documented so that anyone can integrate anything they want once ShipReq gets traction.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It also \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"might\"}]},{\"lit\":\" make sense to try to make this VCS-agnostic too. Actually, nah, the idea that the subset of paying users I'm going to be getting in the next 2 years are going to need a VCS other than Git integrated in completely unrealistic.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"This will need to be highly-configurable. There are so many different git workflows out there, and even so many different ways of using ShipReq. Users should be able to completely configure:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"which branches/tags are monitored per context\"}],[{\"lit\":\"the commit verbs and actions\"}],[{\"lit\":\"which Git users correspond to which ShipReq users. Should be many-to-many. (Eg. of why not many-to-one = pair programming)\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"How to handle commits/tags that later disappear?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I just realised! In addition to git commits, PRs should also receive the same (similar?) treatment! For example, the git commits might contain no info about ShipReq but a PR might be created that says something like \"},{\"mono\":\"Closes FR-xx\"},{\"lit\":\" or whatever. Maybe the concept should remain the same except commits and PRs should be deduped by removing the commits that are already covered by the PR. Similarly, maybe if all commits in a PR refer to the same req, then the PR should be added (and then the commits removed) so just the PR is shown. (?)\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"And similarly, if enabled by configuration, ShipReq should also show the Github issues that reference a req. This is lower priority.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Key takeaways\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Certain verbs should add and/or remove certain tags from reqs\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Certain verbs should only take affect when they appear on certain branches\"}],[{\"lit\":\"References from ShipReq to commits should be shown regardless of the branch\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If possible, turn refs in Github into links back to ShipReq\"}],[{\"lit\":\"handle commits/tags that later disappear\"}]]}]}}}",
