    < ready_for_dev\\nanalysed       > rejected\\nimplemented    < needs_analysis\\nimplemented    < ready_for_dev\\nimplemented    > rejected\\nneeds_analysis > ready_for_dev\\nneeds_analysis > rejected\\nready_for_dev  > rejected\"}},{\"lit\":\"Am I creating a poset? Refl & anti-symm hold. Transitivity?\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[\"render\"],\"code\":\"rankdir=TB\\nedge [dir=back]\\n\\nneeds_analysis -> analysed\\nneeds_analysis -> implemented\\nneeds_analysis -> ready_for_dev\\nneeds_analysis -> rejected\\n\\nready_for_dev  -> analysed\\nready_for_dev  -> implemented\\nready_for_dev  -> rejected\\n\\nimplemented    -> analysed\\nimplemented    -> rejected\\n\\nanalysed       -> rejected\\n\\n// 1. needs_analysis -> *\\n// 2. ready_for_dev  -> *\\n// 3. implemented    -> *\\n// 4. analysed       -> *\\n// 5. rejected       -> *\",\"lang\":\"dot\"}},{\"lit\":\"System needs to alert user to what's missing in their list and (if there is default handling) show them the default results.\"},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"What about...\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"children that have multiple values?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"deriving a multi-value result?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"user input? Allow users to manually specify (i.e. override) or not? Or make configurable?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"handle empties? eg. allow a rule to say ∅ + * = ∅?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"derivation simply being a sum and displaying as a bar (like the eg in \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":108}},{\"lit\":\")\"}],[{\"lit\":\"a single field definition resulting in two virtual fields, one with the values, and another with composite-colour-bars? It's really a \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"view\"}]},{\"lit\":\" change, with the same content and even conceptual field. How can users change the way they want to view the same cell? Maybe add a little config with checkboxes like \\\"show percentage bars\\\" in the req table? But then what about req detail? It definitely shouldn't be part of the field's config. What about the idea of global hidden state per field, and you can single-click the field to toggle through view styles? Actually this is a similar problem as \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":111}},{\"lit\":\" - changing the view of a column in ReqTable.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"using derivative tags for versions. That might need to work in both directions. Eg MF1 -> FR1, if MF1 tagged with v1.2 then FR1 gets it too. And the opposite direction, if FR1 has the tag and MF1 doesn't, then MF1 should get it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"provenance. It would be pretty frustrating if a req has a tag and the user isn't able to figure out why. We need to allow users to see where derived tags come from.\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"Multi-value results\"}]},{\"lit\":\"There might be very legitimate cases where you want the result to be multiple values. Maybe something like \"},{\"mono\":\"#in_testing #pending_security_review\"},{\"lit\":\". An easy modification to the above would be to allow partial semigroup rules, and if a rule for x and y doesn't exist, then the result is simply \"},{\"mono\":\"#x #y\"},{\"lit\":\" (i.e. \"},{\"mono\":\"#x + #y\"},{\"lit\":\" implicitly / by-default \"},{\"mono\":\"= #x #y\"},{\"lit\":\").\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I wonder how generalised that concept is? \"},{\"mono\":\"A + A = Set[A]\"},{\"lit\":\"? If it were that flexible you'd need to prove infinite loops aren't possible.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"What about \"},{\"mono\":\"A + A = Option[A]\"},{\"lit\":\"? That would allow tags to vanish from calculation which seems bizarre.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":713,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T05:27:25.879387Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":108},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"The need for this feature comes about pretty quickly once you've got more than a non-trivial amount of requirements in the system. When everything is in a flat list/grid, it's so hard to know what the hell is going on. I'm not gonna sit there and read everything (which means I'm not going to read anything cos understanding one line doesn't help me understand the rest - it doesn't scale). I know for a fact that all of my content is hierarchical. Hierarchies are a great solution to this problem because it would allow me to look at the bunch of high-level stuff, and then drill into detail as I desire. So the abstract feature I need is comprised of the following:\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"present a DAG/tree of content so that the DAG/tree structure is visible to the user\"}],[{\"lit\":\"allow me to {collapse,expand} {single,multiple,all} rows in the req table\"}],[{\"lit\":\"allow the DAG/tree structure to be configurable - eg. implication, req codes, statuses\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"Status is an interesting one. I might want to view all my content grouped by MF and then status. Something like this:\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"+ MF-1\\n- MF-2\\n  + needs_analysis (4) (25%)\\n  - ready_for_dev (4) (25%)\\n    - FR-1\\n    - FR-8\\n    - FR-11\\n    - FR-13\\n  + implemented (8) (50%)\\n+ MF-3\\n+ MF-4\"}},{\"lit\":\"I don't know if this will overlap with \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" or not, but it would also be pretty nice if I could see the status breakdown in a single cell without having to expand the MFs. An idea could be just a coloured bar. Example:\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"+---+------+--------------------------+\\n| + | MF-1 | [###GREEN###|RED|#GRAY#] |\\n| + | MF-2 | [######GREEN######|RED#] |\\n| + | MF-3 | [GREEN|#####RED#####|GR] |\\n+---+------+--------------------------+\"}},{\"lit\":\"So, it looks like:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"tags are like \"},{\"mono\":\"GROUP-BY\"},{\"lit\":\"s that can be nested\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Req codes are obvious (in isolation at least)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Implication tree is a must.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I just wonder about imp-field values (now that they're different from imp-tree). I think it's a \\\"must\\\" too. Actually they definitely are. If I'm interested in grouping by MF, I don't care how the implication was specified, I just want to see everything in that umbrella.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Tag groupings should be composable with imp-tree/field groupings (eg. version and then MF-tree)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Req types should be grouping criteria too\"}]]},{\"h4\":[{\"lit\":\"ReqTable?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I'm pretty sure this should go into ReqTable.\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"It's purpose is bulk / multiple reqs. This feature adheres to that.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If I made a completely different screen I'd still want to have all of the req table functionality anyway (especially it's flexibility in letting me see specific aspects of reqs in bulk)\"}],[{\"lit\":\"The view would have to be drastically different to justify adding a new screen. That means not a grid. Maybe there is some need for this but it would be insanity to only do that and not modify the ReqTable. It would mean users would find exactly what they're looking for on one screen and then have to manually try to reconstruct the same filter on the ReqTable. Yuk.\"}]]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":714,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T05:29:28.323992Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqCreate\":{\"reqId\":113,\"reqTypeId\":10,\"values\":[]}}}",
    "{\"#\":715,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T05:29:45.203632Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":113,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Collapsible trees (Q& A)\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":716,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T05:29:54.668892Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":113},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":108}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":717,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T06:09:37.532182Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":113},\"value\":[{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences that the new feature could cause?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I see a potential conflict between where I imagine the collapse/expand buttons will go, and the existing row-selection checkboxes\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about screen clutter - where will the collapse/expand-all buttons go? what about the grouping criteria?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about the increased complexity for users\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If we have a constraint that the grouping criteria is also the leading sorting criteria, that might simplify things\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect most excites you?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It will be really nice to be able to browse. I'm looking forward to that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"But honestly, the idea of the tag-percentage bars makes me actually excited. I love it! It's gonna be a really nice, quick easy way to gauge progress (usually of an MF). A huge part of the goals of ShipReq are to be able to have a shit-ton of complex data, and be able to work with it, and comprehend it really quickly and easily.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect will be most valuable to you? Least valuable?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The most valuable aspects:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"being able to see what's there, what's not, really quickly\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to see where things are up to, and understand what the next steps are\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to read requirements as easily as a book, but tree-structured so one can focus on their area of interest\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to select my own aspect (eg. some tag of mine) and understand the breakdown in specific contexts\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"The least:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I don't know. Maybe none? I can't think of anything non-critical.\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What is the real reason for wanting to solve this problem?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Enabling quick comprehensibility for users.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can we copy something that already exists?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Not really. When sorting by req-code we generate a tree in a column but we need much more than that, and that solution is really simple and hard-coded to req codes. We'd actually have to discard a bunch of that functionality and re-implement req code trees using this new feature.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution? What are the expectations?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I should be easily able to browse my requirements in a structured way. Not very quantitative but I'm having this problem with ShipReq requirements themselves in ShipReq, so I've got real data and I'm a real user. My own experience with the new feature will be enough to gauge it's success.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I expect that I'll be able to look at all reqs in the req table (i.e. no filter), and see a reasonable amount of rows.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Scenario 1:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Working on v2.2; what am I doing? How am I going? What's next?\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Rows will mostly be MFs. I'd sort by a version tag so that the stuff I'm interested in right now would be in the middle (between done and postponed). In fact I would ONLY want to see MFs, I wouldn't want to see interviews even if they imply MFs. I'd rather just see MFs, then expand an MF to see the IV that implied it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Once I click an MF I'm not sure if I want to see a flat list, or whether it should be a tree by implication. There might be cases where the flat list sorted by a status tag would be useful. But really, if \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is done then looking at just the next level in the implication tree should be enough because those nodes should have a status (or status combo bar) that represents the status of everything in that tree. In which case I'd just browse the few I cared about that had certain statuses. In fact, I may even want to filter a few statuses out, else it might be too noisy. YES! Actually, let's say I filter out \\\"rejected\\\", I'd want \\\"rejected\\\" removed from status bars, and I'd want nodes that are 100% rejected to be removed entirely. Holy shit that would be beautiful and powerful.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I could add some filters (like tag filters described above), and filter MF's by version, save it as a view and I'd easily be able to solve my problem of not knowing where I'm up to in my work.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Depending on my mood, I might prefer to pick up a dev task or an analysis task. I should be able to add a tag filter and enjoy all the same benefits as above. Really it's the same need: scope, browse, comprehend.\"}]]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":718,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T06:38:40.986951Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":113},\"value\":[{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences that the new feature could cause?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I see a potential conflict between where I imagine the collapse/expand buttons will go, and the existing row-selection checkboxes\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about screen clutter - where will the collapse/expand-all buttons go? what about the grouping criteria?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about the increased complexity for users\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If we have a constraint that the grouping criteria is also the leading sorting criteria, that might simplify things\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect most excites you?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It will be really nice to be able to browse. I'm looking forward to that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"But honestly, the idea of the tag-percentage bars makes me actually excited. I love it! It's gonna be a really nice, quick easy way to gauge progress (usually of an MF). A huge part of the goals of ShipReq are to be able to have a shit-ton of complex data, and be able to work with it, and comprehend it really quickly and easily.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect will be most valuable to you? Least valuable?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The most valuable aspects:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"being able to see what's there, what's not, really quickly\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to see where things are up to, and understand what the next steps are\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to read requirements as easily as a book, but tree-structured so one can focus on their area of interest\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to select my own aspect (eg. some tag of mine) and understand the breakdown in specific contexts\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"The least:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I don't know. Maybe none? I can't think of anything non-critical.\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What is the real reason for wanting to solve this problem?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Enabling quick comprehensibility for users.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can we copy something that already exists?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Not really. When sorting by req-code we generate a tree in a column but we need much more than that, and that solution is really simple and hard-coded to req codes. We'd actually have to discard a bunch of that functionality and re-implement req code trees using this new feature.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution? What are the expectations?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I should be easily able to browse my requirements in a structured way. Not very quantitative but I'm having this problem with ShipReq requirements themselves in ShipReq, so I've got real data and I'm a real user. My own experience with the new feature will be enough to gauge it's success.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I expect that I'll be able to look at all reqs in the req table (i.e. no filter), and see a reasonable amount of rows.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Scenario:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Working on v2.2; what am I doing? How am I going? What's next?\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Rows will mostly be MFs. I'd sort by a version tag so that the stuff I'm interested in right now would be in the middle (between done and postponed). In fact I would ONLY want to see MFs, I wouldn't want to see interviews even if they imply MFs. I'd rather just see MFs, then expand an MF to see the IV that implied it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Once I click an MF I'm not sure if I want to see a flat list, or whether it should be a tree by implication. There might be cases where the flat list sorted by a status tag would be useful. But really, if \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is done then looking at just the next level in the implication tree should be enough because those nodes should have a status (or status combo bar) that represents the status of everything in that tree. In which case I'd just browse the few I cared about that had certain statuses. In fact, I may even want to filter a few statuses out, else it might be too noisy. YES! Actually, let's say I filter out \\\"rejected\\\", I'd want \\\"rejected\\\" removed from status bars, and I'd want nodes that are 100% rejected to be removed entirely. Holy shit that would be beautiful and powerful.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I could add some filters (like tag filters described above), and filter MF's by version, save it as a view and I'd easily be able to solve my problem of not knowing where I'm up to in my work.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Depending on my mood, I might prefer to pick up a dev task or an analysis task. I should be able to add a tag filter and enjoy all the same benefits as above. Really it's the same need: scope, browse, comprehend.\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Should the collapse/expand state be saved as part of saved views?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"That's a tricky one. I don't think it's a good idea to retain collapse state literally by ReqId or similar because it's too fickle, plus what about when new reqs are added? Manually expand and re-save all the time? That strongly goes against ShipReq's core values of no-busywork.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"We could default to all collapsed or all expanded. Easy. But which would we choose? There are pros and cons to both. Actually this might be an area where it'd be smart to just pick a default, and leave it alone until we have opposing customers. After all there's an expand/collapse all button for if anyone wants the opposite of the default. And seeing as the goal of this is simplification and gradual, targeted increases in information, defaulting to AllCollapsed makes the most sense.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Otherwise, we could try to smart about it. If everything's expanded when we save state, we save it as AllExpanded. Vica-versa for collapsed. When the tree is partially expanded we could just retain whatever the previous value was. I'm not sure it's worth it though and we could even make this change later as an intermediate step between no-control and full-control.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Does this feature need to wait until \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is analysed or implemented?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Technically, I don't think so. Derivative tags will only affect the value of tag fields. Even when we're grouping by tag and showing tag combo bars, that's not affected by how tag fields get their content. \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Unless\"}]},{\"lit\":\" \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" introduces some new quantum/multi state that tag fields can be in. But even then, we already support multiple tags per field, so we'd only be affected if tags in tag fields were to start having weights (eg. \\\"34 done, 3 pending\\\" as opposed to just \\\"done pending\\\").\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So actually, \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"yes\"}]},{\"lit\":\". Let's just wait until that specific detail has been analysed.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Will you need keyboard shortcuts for collapse/expand?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"For each row, absolutely. Not sure about all. We should add it for good measure. And I guess now we'll need to start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help modal, or maybe just show keyboard shortcuts on hover? Could do both. Actually, let's definitely start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help page; there may be shortcuts in future where adding a hover isn't feasible. Plus it's a standard practice. Could put it next to \\\"Send Feedback\\\" in the menu.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"How will imp-field trees differ from imp-trees?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Imp trees are unidirectional. The tree's will only look forward. Actually that's not tree, we should allow backwards looking trees too, simply for flexibility. I'm not sure when that would ever come in handy though.... Actually, maybe when I'm focused on a single req and want to start browsing back up the tree to understand something about it. I've done this before but I had to keep clicking on reqs in the req detail imp graph page to find what I wanted. So let's definitely allow backwards facing trees. If it's really useful we can even add a button to the req detail page that when clicked, takes you to the req table page, filters only on that req, expands all and let's you browse it's reverse imp tree.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Holy shit, how do we now distinguish top-level filters from tree children filters??! Do we need to? I hope not. Let's see.... we should actually just be able to filter by \\\"implies:ReqId\\\" in the above scenario. Yeah we should be fine with just one filter.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So that's normal imp trees but what about imp-field trees. The formula has changed since \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":103}},{\"lit\":\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So for the top level rows, (immediate) backwards implication should as if it's forward. So \"},{\"mono\":\"FR2 -> MF1 -> FR3\"},{\"lit\":\" should be as if it were \"},{\"mono\":\"MF1 -> FR-{2,3}\"},{\"lit\":\". What about transitivity? What about forward-facing tree on external sources?\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":719,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T06:54:55.132393Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":113},\"value\":[{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences that the new feature could cause?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I see a potential conflict between where I imagine the collapse/expand buttons will go, and the existing row-selection checkboxes\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about screen clutter - where will the collapse/expand-all buttons go? what about the grouping criteria?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about the increased complexity for users\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If we have a constraint that the grouping criteria is also the leading sorting criteria, that might simplify things\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect most excites you?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It will be really nice to be able to browse. I'm looking forward to that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"But honestly, the idea of the tag-percentage bars makes me actually excited. I love it! It's gonna be a really nice, quick easy way to gauge progress (usually of an MF). A huge part of the goals of ShipReq are to be able to have a shit-ton of complex data, and be able to work with it, and comprehend it really quickly and easily.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect will be most valuable to you? Least valuable?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The most valuable aspects:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"being able to see what's there, what's not, really quickly\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to see where things are up to, and understand what the next steps are\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to read requirements as easily as a book, but tree-structured so one can focus on their area of interest\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to select my own aspect (eg. some tag of mine) and understand the breakdown in specific contexts\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"The least:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I don't know. Maybe none? I can't think of anything non-critical.\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What is the real reason for wanting to solve this problem?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Enabling quick comprehensibility for users.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can we copy something that already exists?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Not really. When sorting by req-code we generate a tree in a column but we need much more than that, and that solution is really simple and hard-coded to req codes. We'd actually have to discard a bunch of that functionality and re-implement req code trees using this new feature.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution? What are the expectations?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I should be easily able to browse my requirements in a structured way. Not very quantitative but I'm having this problem with ShipReq requirements themselves in ShipReq, so I've got real data and I'm a real user. My own experience with the new feature will be enough to gauge it's success.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I expect that I'll be able to look at all reqs in the req table (i.e. no filter), and see a reasonable amount of rows.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Scenario:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Working on v2.2; what am I doing? How am I going? What's next?\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Rows will mostly be MFs. I'd sort by a version tag so that the stuff I'm interested in right now would be in the middle (between done and postponed). In fact I would ONLY want to see MFs, I wouldn't want to see interviews even if they imply MFs. I'd rather just see MFs, then expand an MF to see the IV that implied it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Once I click an MF I'm not sure if I want to see a flat list, or whether it should be a tree by implication. There might be cases where the flat list sorted by a status tag would be useful. But really, if \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is done then looking at just the next level in the implication tree should be enough because those nodes should have a status (or status combo bar) that represents the status of everything in that tree. In which case I'd just browse the few I cared about that had certain statuses. In fact, I may even want to filter a few statuses out, else it might be too noisy. YES! Actually, let's say I filter out \\\"rejected\\\", I'd want \\\"rejected\\\" removed from status bars, and I'd want nodes that are 100% rejected to be removed entirely. Holy shit that would be beautiful and powerful.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I could add some filters (like tag filters described above), and filter MF's by version, save it as a view and I'd easily be able to solve my problem of not knowing where I'm up to in my work.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Depending on my mood, I might prefer to pick up a dev task or an analysis task. I should be able to add a tag filter and enjoy all the same benefits as above. Really it's the same need: scope, browse, comprehend.\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Should the collapse/expand state be saved as part of saved views?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"That's a tricky one. I don't think it's a good idea to retain collapse state literally by ReqId or similar because it's too fickle, plus what about when new reqs are added? Manually expand and re-save all the time? That strongly goes against ShipReq's core values of no-busywork.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"We could default to all collapsed or all expanded. Easy. But which would we choose? There are pros and cons to both. Actually this might be an area where it'd be smart to just pick a default, and leave it alone until we have opposing customers. After all there's an expand/collapse all button for if anyone wants the opposite of the default. And seeing as the goal of this is simplification and gradual, targeted increases in information, defaulting to AllCollapsed makes the most sense.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Otherwise, we could try to smart about it. If everything's expanded when we save state, we save it as AllExpanded. Vica-versa for collapsed. When the tree is partially expanded we could just retain whatever the previous value was. I'm not sure it's worth it though and we could even make this change later as an intermediate step between no-control and full-control.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Does this feature need to wait until \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is analysed or implemented?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Technically, I don't think so. Derivative tags will only affect the value of tag fields. Even when we're grouping by tag and showing tag combo bars, that's not affected by how tag fields get their content. \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Unless\"}]},{\"lit\":\" \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" introduces some new quantum/multi state that tag fields can be in. But even then, we already support multiple tags per field, so we'd only be affected if tags in tag fields were to start having weights (eg. \\\"34 done, 3 pending\\\" as opposed to just \\\"done pending\\\").\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So actually, \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"yes\"}]},{\"lit\":\". Let's just wait until that specific detail has been analysed.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Will you need keyboard shortcuts for collapse/expand?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"For each row, absolutely. Not sure about all. We should add it for good measure. And I guess now we'll need to start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help modal, or maybe just show keyboard shortcuts on hover? Could do both. Actually, let's definitely start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help page; there may be shortcuts in future where adding a hover isn't feasible. Plus it's a standard practice. Could put it next to \\\"Send Feedback\\\" in the menu.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"How will imp-field trees differ from imp-trees?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Imp trees are unidirectional. The tree's will only look forward. Actually that's not tree, we should allow backwards looking trees too, simply for flexibility. I'm not sure when that would ever come in handy though.... Actually, maybe when I'm focused on a single req and want to start browsing back up the tree to understand something about it. I've done this before but I had to keep clicking on reqs in the req detail imp graph page to find what I wanted. So let's definitely allow backwards facing trees. If it's really useful we can even add a button to the req detail page that when clicked, takes you to the req table page, filters only on that req, expands all and let's you browse it's reverse imp tree.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Holy shit, how do we now distinguish top-level filters from tree children filters??! Do we need to? I hope not. Let's see.... we should actually just be able to filter by \\\"implies:ReqId\\\" in the above scenario. Yeah we should be fine with just one filter.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So that's normal imp trees but what about imp-field trees. The formula has changed since \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":103}},{\"lit\":\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So for the top level rows, (immediate) backwards implication should as if it's forward. So \"},{\"mono\":\"FR2 -> MF1 -> FR3\"},{\"lit\":\" should be as if it were \"},{\"mono\":\"MF1 -> FR-{2,3}\"},{\"lit\":\". What about transitivity? What about forward-facing tree on external sources?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Say we had:\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[\"render\"],\"code\":\"node[style=filled fillcolor=\\\"#dddddd\\\"]\\nMF2,MF4,MF8 [fillcolor=\\\"#88ee00\\\"]\\nIV6 -> IV1 -> MF2 -> FR3\\nMF4 -> IV5 -> FR3\\nIV6 -> IV7 -> MF8\",\"lang\":\"dot\"}},{\"lit\":\"I expect to see\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"* MF2\\n  * IV1 (backwards)\\n    * IV6 (backwards)\\n      * IV7 ????????????????????????????? no\\n  * FR3\\n    * IV5 ???????????????????????????????\\n* MF4\\n  * IV5\\n    * FR3\\n      * MF2 ?????????????????????????????\\n* MF8\\n  * IV7\\n    * IV6\\n      * IV1 ?????????????????????????????\",\"lang\":\"md\"}},{\"lit\":\"Property: I expect when I filter req table in flat mode by impField=X1, every row I see should be somewhere in the tree of X1 when it's top-level and I'm grouping by impField:X.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":720,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-03T07:03:19.026250Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":113},\"value\":[{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences that the new feature could cause?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I see a potential conflict between where I imagine the collapse/expand buttons will go, and the existing row-selection checkboxes\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about screen clutter - where will the collapse/expand-all buttons go? what about the grouping criteria?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about the increased complexity for users\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If we have a constraint that the grouping criteria is also the leading sorting criteria, that might simplify things\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect most excites you?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It will be really nice to be able to browse. I'm looking forward to that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"But honestly, the idea of the tag-percentage bars makes me actually excited. I love it! It's gonna be a really nice, quick easy way to gauge progress (usually of an MF). A huge part of the goals of ShipReq are to be able to have a shit-ton of complex data, and be able to work with it, and comprehend it really quickly and easily.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect will be most valuable to you? Least valuable?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The most valuable aspects:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"being able to see what's there, what's not, really quickly\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to see where things are up to, and understand what the next steps are\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to read requirements as easily as a book, but tree-structured so one can focus on their area of interest\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to select my own aspect (eg. some tag of mine) and understand the breakdown in specific contexts\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"The least:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I don't know. Maybe none? I can't think of anything non-critical.\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"What is the real reason for wanting to solve this problem?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Enabling quick comprehensibility for users.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Can we copy something that already exists?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Not really. When sorting by req-code we generate a tree in a column but we need much more than that, and that solution is really simple and hard-coded to req codes. We'd actually have to discard a bunch of that functionality and re-implement req code trees using this new feature.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution? What are the expectations?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I should be easily able to browse my requirements in a structured way. Not very quantitative but I'm having this problem with ShipReq requirements themselves in ShipReq, so I've got real data and I'm a real user. My own experience with the new feature will be enough to gauge it's success.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I expect that I'll be able to look at all reqs in the req table (i.e. no filter), and see a reasonable amount of rows.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Scenario:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Working on v2.2; what am I doing? How am I going? What's next?\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Rows will mostly be MFs. I'd sort by a version tag so that the stuff I'm interested in right now would be in the middle (between done and postponed). In fact I would ONLY want to see MFs, I wouldn't want to see interviews even if they imply MFs. I'd rather just see MFs, then expand an MF to see the IV that implied it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Once I click an MF I'm not sure if I want to see a flat list, or whether it should be a tree by implication. There might be cases where the flat list sorted by a status tag would be useful. But really, if \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is done then looking at just the next level in the implication tree should be enough because those nodes should have a status (or status combo bar) that represents the status of everything in that tree. In which case I'd just browse the few I cared about that had certain statuses. In fact, I may even want to filter a few statuses out, else it might be too noisy. YES! Actually, let's say I filter out \\\"rejected\\\", I'd want \\\"rejected\\\" removed from status bars, and I'd want nodes that are 100% rejected to be removed entirely. Holy shit that would be beautiful and powerful.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I could add some filters (like tag filters described above), and filter MF's by version, save it as a view and I'd easily be able to solve my problem of not knowing where I'm up to in my work.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Depending on my mood, I might prefer to pick up a dev task or an analysis task. I should be able to add a tag filter and enjoy all the same benefits as above. Really it's the same need: scope, browse, comprehend.\"}]]},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Should the collapse/expand state be saved as part of saved views?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"That's a tricky one. I don't think it's a good idea to retain collapse state literally by ReqId or similar because it's too fickle, plus what about when new reqs are added? Manually expand and re-save all the time? That strongly goes against ShipReq's core values of no-busywork.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"We could default to all collapsed or all expanded. Easy. But which would we choose? There are pros and cons to both. Actually this might be an area where it'd be smart to just pick a default, and leave it alone until we have opposing customers. After all there's an expand/collapse all button for if anyone wants the opposite of the default. And seeing as the goal of this is simplification and gradual, targeted increases in information, defaulting to AllCollapsed makes the most sense.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Otherwise, we could try to smart about it. If everything's expanded when we save state, we save it as AllExpanded. Vica-versa for collapsed. When the tree is partially expanded we could just retain whatever the previous value was. I'm not sure it's worth it though and we could even make this change later as an intermediate step between no-control and full-control.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Does this feature need to wait until \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is analysed or implemented?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Technically, I don't think so. Derivative tags will only affect the value of tag fields. Even when we're grouping by tag and showing tag combo bars, that's not affected by how tag fields get their content. \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Unless\"}]},{\"lit\":\" \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" introduces some new quantum/multi state that tag fields can be in. But even then, we already support multiple tags per field, so we'd only be affected if tags in tag fields were to start having weights (eg. \\\"34 done, 3 pending\\\" as opposed to just \\\"done pending\\\").\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So actually, \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"yes\"}]},{\"lit\":\". Let's just wait until that specific detail has been analysed.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"Will you need keyboard shortcuts for collapse/expand?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"For each row, absolutely. Not sure about all. We should add it for good measure. And I guess now we'll need to start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help modal, or maybe just show keyboard shortcuts on hover? Could do both. Actually, let's definitely start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help page; there may be shortcuts in future where adding a hover isn't feasible. Plus it's a standard practice. Could put it next to \\\"Send Feedback\\\" in the menu.\"},{\"h3\":[{\"lit\":\"How will imp-field trees differ from imp-trees?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Imp trees are unidirectional. The tree's will only look forward. Actually that's not tree, we should allow backwards looking trees too, simply for flexibility. I'm not sure when that would ever come in handy though.... Actually, maybe when I'm focused on a single req and want to start browsing back up the tree to understand something about it. I've done this before but I had to keep clicking on reqs in the req detail imp graph page to find what I wanted. So let's definitely allow backwards facing trees. If it's really useful we can even add a button to the req detail page that when clicked, takes you to the req table page, filters only on that req, expands all and let's you browse it's reverse imp tree.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Holy shit, how do we now distinguish top-level filters from tree children filters??! Do we need to? I hope not. Let's see.... we should actually just be able to filter by \\\"implies:ReqId\\\" in the above scenario. Yeah we should be fine with just one filter.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So that's normal imp trees but what about imp-field trees. The formula has changed since \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":103}},{\"lit\":\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So for the top level rows, (immediate) backwards implication should as if it's forward. So \"},{\"mono\":\"FR2 -> MF1 -> FR3\"},{\"lit\":\" should be as if it were \"},{\"mono\":\"MF1 -> FR-{2,3}\"},{\"lit\":\". What about transitivity? What about forward-facing tree on external sources?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Say we had:\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[\"render\"],\"code\":\"node[style=filled fillcolor=\\\"#dddddd\\\"]\\nMF1,MF2,MF3 [fillcolor=\\\"#88ee00\\\"]\\nFR1 [label=\\\"FR1\\\\n(1,2)\\\"]\\nIV1 [label=\\\"IV1\\\\n(1)\\\"]\\nIV2 [label=\\\"IV2\\\\n(1,2)\\\"]\\nIV3 [label=\\\"IV3\\\\n(1,3)\\\"]\\nIV4 [label=\\\"IV4\\\\n(3)\\\"]\\n\\nIV3 -> IV1 -> MF1 -> FR1\\nMF2 -> IV2 -> FR1\\nIV3 -> IV4 -> MF3\",\"lang\":\"dot\"}},{\"lit\":\"I expect to see\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"* MF1\\n  * IV1 (backwards)\\n    * IV3 (backwards)\\n      * IV4 ????????????????????????????? no\\n  * FR1\\n    * IV2 ???????????????????????????????\\n* MF2\\n  * IV2\\n    * FR1\\n      * MF2 ?????????????????????????????\\n* MF3\\n  * IV4\\n    * IV3\\n      * IV1 ?????????????????????????????\",\"lang\":\"md\"}},{\"**\":[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Property:\"}]}]},{\"lit\":\" I expect when I filter req table in flat mode by impField=X1, every row I see should be somewhere in the tree of X1 when it's top-level and I'm grouping by impField:X.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Meaning that the following reqs must be under their MF trees:\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"MF1 - FR1, IV-{1,2,3}\\nMF2 - FR1, IV-2\\nMF3 - IV-{3,4}\"}}]}}}",
