    "{\"#\":735,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T01:46:54.595882Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":114,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Derivative tags (Q & A)\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":736,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T01:47:00.900976Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":114},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":109}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":737,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T02:07:52.367504Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":114},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Should we have multiple weighted values instead of a consolidation?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"So instead of (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev = ready_for_dev), what would it be like to just retain (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev) as the value? Well for starters, the req would effectively have both tags (completed, ready_for_dev). Bubbling this up to the top you'd end up with MF's having nearly all the tags which seems like it'd be useless. I think just choosing one tag and displaying the breakdown/calculation is the way to go.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Apart from it being informational, what else would it affect? It would affect filtering. So filtering by rejected would now include all the non-rejected MFs and a bunch of intermediate (possibly valid) intermediate reqs too. That sounds like shit.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I think it's a clear \\\"no\\\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Don't forget that when a semigroup rule for two values doesn't exist, we simply take both without consolidation. That's orthogonal to this question and decision.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when there's no tag in a child?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when a child has multiple tags?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"We've studied derivative statuses, what about versions?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should we show, where?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"reqtable vs req detail\"}],[{\"lit\":\"subject tag field vs anything else?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"In req detail (at least), it would be cool to display the final tag value, and then next to it, a colour bar indicating the makeup.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Req table is a different kettle of fish because conciseness matters.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Hell we could even use the cell \"},{\"mono\":\"bottom-border\"},{\"lit\":\" to render the bar without padding. That's pretty concise.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":738,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T02:08:06.438707Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"->\",\"id\":{\"gr\":114},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":113}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":739,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T02:09:26.398382Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":113},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences that the new feature could cause?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I see a potential conflict between where I imagine the collapse/expand buttons will go, and the existing row-selection checkboxes\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about screen clutter - where will the collapse/expand-all buttons go? what about the grouping criteria?\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I'm worried about the increased complexity for users\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If we have a constraint that the grouping criteria is also the leading sorting criteria, that might simplify things\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect most excites you?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"It will be really nice to be able to browse. I'm looking forward to that.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"But honestly, the idea of the tag-percentage bars makes me actually excited. I love it! It's gonna be a really nice, quick easy way to gauge progress (usually of an MF). A huge part of the goals of ShipReq are to be able to have a shit-ton of complex data, and be able to work with it, and comprehend it really quickly and easily.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect will be most valuable to you? Least valuable?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"The most valuable aspects:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"being able to see what's there, what's not, really quickly\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to see where things are up to, and understand what the next steps are\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to read requirements as easily as a book, but tree-structured so one can focus on their area of interest\"}],[{\"lit\":\"being able to select my own aspect (eg. some tag of mine) and understand the breakdown in specific contexts\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"The least:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"I don't know. Maybe none? I can't think of anything non-critical.\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What is the real reason for wanting to solve this problem?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Enabling quick comprehensibility for users.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Can we copy something that already exists?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Not really. When sorting by req-code we generate a tree in a column but we need much more than that, and that solution is really simple and hard-coded to req codes. We'd actually have to discard a bunch of that functionality and re-implement req code trees using this new feature.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution? What are the expectations?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"I should be easily able to browse my requirements in a structured way. Not very quantitative but I'm having this problem with ShipReq requirements themselves in ShipReq, so I've got real data and I'm a real user. My own experience with the new feature will be enough to gauge it's success.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I expect that I'll be able to look at all reqs in the req table (i.e. no filter), and see a reasonable amount of rows.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Scenario:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" Working on v2.2; what am I doing? How am I going? What's next?\"},{\"ol\":[[{\"lit\":\"Rows will mostly be MFs. I'd sort by a version tag so that the stuff I'm interested in right now would be in the middle (between done and postponed). In fact I would ONLY want to see MFs, I wouldn't want to see interviews even if they imply MFs. I'd rather just see MFs, then expand an MF to see the IV that implied it.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Once I click an MF I'm not sure if I want to see a flat list, or whether it should be a tree by implication. There might be cases where the flat list sorted by a status tag would be useful. But really, if \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is done then looking at just the next level in the implication tree should be enough because those nodes should have a status (or status combo bar) that represents the status of everything in that tree. In which case I'd just browse the few I cared about that had certain statuses. In fact, I may even want to filter a few statuses out, else it might be too noisy. YES! Actually, let's say I filter out \\\"rejected\\\", I'd want \\\"rejected\\\" removed from status bars, and I'd want nodes that are 100% rejected to be removed entirely. Holy shit that would be beautiful and powerful.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I could add some filters (like tag filters described above), and filter MF's by version, save it as a view and I'd easily be able to solve my problem of not knowing where I'm up to in my work.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Depending on my mood, I might prefer to pick up a dev task or an analysis task. I should be able to add a tag filter and enjoy all the same benefits as above. Really it's the same need: scope, browse, comprehend.\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Should the collapse/expand state be saved as part of saved views?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"That's a tricky one. I don't think it's a good idea to retain collapse state literally by ReqId or similar because it's too fickle, plus what about when new reqs are added? Manually expand and re-save all the time? That strongly goes against ShipReq's core values of no-busywork.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"We could default to all collapsed or all expanded. Easy. But which would we choose? There are pros and cons to both. Actually this might be an area where it'd be smart to just pick a default, and leave it alone until we have opposing customers. After all there's an expand/collapse all button for if anyone wants the opposite of the default. And seeing as the goal of this is simplification and gradual, targeted increases in information, defaulting to AllCollapsed makes the most sense.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Otherwise, we could try to smart about it. If everything's expanded when we save state, we save it as AllExpanded. Vica-versa for collapsed. When the tree is partially expanded we could just retain whatever the previous value was. I'm not sure it's worth it though and we could even make this change later as an intermediate step between no-control and full-control.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Does this feature need to wait until \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" is analysed or implemented?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Technically, I don't think so. Derivative tags will only affect the value of tag fields. Even when we're grouping by tag and showing tag combo bars, that's not affected by how tag fields get their content. \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"Unless\"}]},{\"lit\":\" \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" introduces some new quantum/multi state that tag fields can be in. But even then, we already support multiple tags per field, so we'd only be affected if tags in tag fields were to start having weights (eg. \\\"34 done, 3 pending\\\" as opposed to just \\\"done pending\\\").\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So actually, \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"yes\"}]},{\"lit\":\". Let's just wait until that specific detail has been analysed.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Update:\"}]},{\"lit\":\" The answer is no. \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":72}},{\"lit\":\" won't result in quantum tags.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Will you need keyboard shortcuts for collapse/expand?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"For each row, absolutely. Not sure about all. We should add it for good measure. And I guess now we'll need to start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help modal, or maybe just show keyboard shortcuts on hover? Could do both. Actually, let's definitely start maintaining a keyboard shortcut help page; there may be shortcuts in future where adding a hover isn't feasible. Plus it's a standard practice. Could put it next to \\\"Send Feedback\\\" in the menu.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"How will imp-field trees differ from imp-trees?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Imp trees are unidirectional. The tree's will only look forward. Actually that's not tree, we should allow backwards looking trees too, simply for flexibility. I'm not sure when that would ever come in handy though.... Actually, maybe when I'm focused on a single req and want to start browsing back up the tree to understand something about it. I've done this before but I had to keep clicking on reqs in the req detail imp graph page to find what I wanted. So let's definitely allow backwards facing trees. If it's really useful we can even add a button to the req detail page that when clicked, takes you to the req table page, filters only on that req, expands all and let's you browse it's reverse imp tree.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Holy shit, how do we now distinguish top-level filters from tree children filters??! Do we need to? I hope not. Let's see.... we should actually just be able to filter by \\\"implies:ReqId\\\" in the above scenario. Yeah we should be fine with just one filter.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So that's normal imp trees but what about imp-field trees. The formula has changed since \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":103}},{\"lit\":\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So for the top level rows, (immediate) backwards implication should as if it's forward. So \"},{\"mono\":\"FR2 -> MF1 -> FR3\"},{\"lit\":\" should be as if it were \"},{\"mono\":\"MF1 -> FR-{2,3}\"},{\"lit\":\". What about transitivity? What about forward-facing tree on external sources?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Say we had:\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[\"render\"],\"code\":\"node[style=filled fillcolor=\\\"#88ee00\\\"]\\nMF1 [label=\\\"MF1\\\\n(1)\\\"]\\nMF2 [label=\\\"MF2\\\\n(2)\\\"]\\nMF3 [label=\\\"MF3\\\\n(3)\\\"]\\nnode [fillcolor=\\\"#dddddd\\\"]\\nFR1 [label=\\\"FR1\\\\n(1,2)\\\"]\\nIV1 [label=\\\"IV1\\\\n(1)\\\"]\\nIV2 [label=\\\"IV2\\\\n(1,2)\\\"]\\nIV3 [label=\\\"IV3\\\\n(1,3)\\\"]\\nIV4 [label=\\\"IV4\\\\n(3)\\\"]\\n\\nIV3 -> IV1 -> MF1 -> FR1\\nMF2 -> IV2 -> FR1\\nIV3 -> IV4 -> MF3\",\"lang\":\"dot\"}},{\"**\":[{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Property:\"}]}]},{\"lit\":\" I expect when I filter req table in flat mode by impField=X1, every row I see should be somewhere in the tree of X1 when it's top-level and I'm grouping by impField:X.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Meaning that the following reqs must be under their MF trees:\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"MF1 - FR1, IV-{1,2,3}\\nMF2 - FR1, IV-2\\nMF3 - IV-{3,4}\"}},{\"lit\":\"I expect to see\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"* MF1\\n  * IV1 (backwards)\\n    * IV3 (backwards)\\n      * IV4 ????????????????????????????? no\\n  * FR1\\n    * IV2 (required by property)\\n* MF2\\n  * IV2\\n    * FR1\\n      * MF1 ????????????????????????????? no\\n* MF3\\n  * IV4\\n    * IV3\\n      * IV1 ????????????????????????????? no - it's doesn't have MF3 in its MF field\",\"lang\":\"md\"}},{\"lit\":\"Similarly, taking the example from \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":102}},{\"lit\":\":\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[\"render\"],\"code\":\"node[style=filled fillcolor=\\\"#88ee00\\\"]\\nMF1 [label=\\\"MF1\\\\n(1)\\\"]\\nMF2 [label=\\\"MF2\\\\n(2,3)\\\"]\\nMF3 [label=\\\"MF3\\\\n(2,3)\\\"]\\nMF4 [label=\\\"MF4\\\\n(4)\\\"]\\nnode [fillcolor=\\\"#dddddd\\\"]\\nFB1 [label=\\\"FB1\\\\n(1,2,3)\\\"]\\nFB2 [label=\\\"FB2\\\\n(1)\\\"]\\nFB3 [label=\\\"FB3\\\\n(1,4)\\\"]\\nFB4 [label=\\\"FB4\\\\n(1,4)\\\"]\\nFR1 [label=\\\"FR1\\\\n(1,4)\\\"]\\nIV1 [label=\\\"IV1\\\\n(1,2,3)\\\"]\\nIV2 [label=\\\"IV2\\\\n(1,2,3)\\\"]\\nUC2 [label=\\\"UC2\\\\n(1,2,3)\\\"]\\n\\n  FB4,MF4 -> FB3 -> FR1\\n  FB2 -> MF1 -> FR1\\n  FB1 -> IV1 -> IV2 -> UC2 -> MF1\\n  UC2 -> MF2 -> MF3\",\"lang\":\"dot\"}},{\"lit\":\"Firstly our property above requires the following:\"},{\"cb\":{\"code\":\"MF1 - FB1,FB2,FB3,FB4,FR1,IV1,IV2,UC2\\nMF2 - FB1,IV1,IV2,MF3,UC2\\nMF3 - FB1,IV1,IV2,MF2,UC2\\nMF4 - FB3,FB4,FR1\"}},{\"lit\":\"should result in\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"* MF1\\n  * FR1\\n    * FB3 (backwards) ???????????? yes, property requires\\n      * FB4 (backwards) ???????????? yes, property requires\\n      * MF4 (backwards) ???????????? no\\n  * FB2 (backwards)\\n  * UC2 (backwards)\\n    * IV2 (backwards)\\n      * IV1 (backwards)\\n        * FB1 (backwards)\\n\\n\\n* MF2\\n  * MF3 ?????????????????\\n    * (mf3 tree) ?????????????\\n  * UC2 (backwards)\\n    * IV2 (backwards)\\n      * IV1 (backwards)\\n        * FB1 (backwards)\\n\\n* MF3\\n  * MF2 (backwards)\\n    * UC2 (backwards) ???????????? yes, property requires\\n      * IV2 (backwards)\\n        * IV1 (backwards)\\n          * FB1 (backwards)\\n\\n* MF4\\n  * FB3\\n    * FR1\\n    * FB4 (backwards)\",\"lang\":\"md\"}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Should it be illegal for reqs \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"not\"}]},{\"lit\":\" covered by the above property to be included?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Yes. ShipReq logic needs to be completely comprehensible to users. If they group by imp-field and then suddenly expanding MF1 is showing content that doesn't have MF1 in its MF field, then it's going to be confusing, and will probably be considered a bug. Answering yes to this question makes the logic really simple from a user's point of view. There's nothing hidden from them, they can see all the data relevant to explain the logic of this feature.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What if we rendered backwards tree forwards from their furthest, relevant leaf?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Let's look at a real example.\"},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"[backwards ok]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\\n      * UC-1: Create and complete requirements (backwards)\\n        * WF-2: Requirements gathering and analysis (backwards)\\n\\n[no backwards]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\\n  * WF-2: Requirements gathering and analysis\\n    * UC-1: Create and complete requirements\\n      * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\",\"lang\":\"md\"}},{\"lit\":\"I think the \"},{\"mono\":\"[no backwards]\"},{\"lit\":\" case makes the most sense. When I'm browsing there is an expectation that each time I descend a level, the scope gets narrower; I'm \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"reducing\"}]},{\"lit\":\" information.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"So yeah, done: all tree branches should be forward facing in terms of implication.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What will happen when reqs in the middle of a tree chain are filtered out?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"So consider the above example from MF-13, what would happen if each req type were filtered out?\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Method 1: Prune entire trees\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"[no FR]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n\\n[no IV]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n\\n[no UC]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\\n\\n[no WF]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\",\"lang\":\"md\"}},{\"__\":[{\"lit\":\"Method 2: reconnect nodes\"}]},{\"cb\":{\"attr\":[],\"code\":\"[no FR]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n\\n[no IV]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * WF-2: Requirements gathering and analysis\\n    * UC-1: Create and complete requirements\\n      * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\\n\\n[no UC]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\\n  * WF-2: Requirements gathering and analysis\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\\n\\n[no WF]\\n* MF-13: Requirement Relationships (i.e. implication)\\n  * IV-26: Consider forward implication when calculating imp fields\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\\n  * UC-1: Create and complete requirements\\n    * FR-5: ReqTable #must be able to display reqs as a tree by implication\",\"lang\":\"md\"}},{\"lit\":\"Method 2 is better. Immediately obvious by method 1's [no IV]: I've filtered out IV's and now my FRs are gone. That would be ridiculous.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Exactly how will nesting group-by criteria will work?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":740,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T02:09:44.736585Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqTagsPatch\":{\"id\":{\"gr\":108},\"patch\":{\"+\":[14],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":741,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T07:11:55.181643Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":114},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Should we have multiple weighted values instead of a consolidation?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"So instead of (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev = ready_for_dev), what would it be like to just retain (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev) as the value? Well for starters, the req would effectively have both tags (completed, ready_for_dev). Bubbling this up to the top you'd end up with MF's having nearly all the tags which seems like it'd be useless. I think just choosing one tag and displaying the breakdown/calculation is the way to go.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Apart from it being informational, what else would it affect? It would affect filtering. So filtering by rejected would now include all the non-rejected MFs and a bunch of intermediate (possibly valid) intermediate reqs too. That sounds like shit.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I think it's a clear \\\"no\\\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Don't forget that when a semigroup rule for two values doesn't exist, we simply take both without consolidation. That's orthogonal to this question and decision.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when there's no tag in a child?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when a child has multiple tags?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"We've studied derivative statuses, what about versions?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should we show, where?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"reqtable vs req detail\"}],[{\"lit\":\"subject tag field vs anything else?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"In req detail (at least), it would be cool to display the final tag value, and then next to it, a colour bar indicating the makeup.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Req table is a different kettle of fish because conciseness matters.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Hell we could even use the cell \"},{\"mono\":\"bottom-border\"},{\"lit\":\" to render the bar without padding. That's pretty concise.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":742,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T07:14:58.129866Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":114},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences this could cause?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Are there any constraints or rules to which the product must conform?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Which aspects of the product are most critical to creating business value?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect of the product most excites you?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect of the product will be most valuable to you? Least valuable?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"How would you judge whether the product is a success?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Should we have multiple weighted values instead of a consolidation?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"So instead of (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev = ready_for_dev), what would it be like to just retain (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev) as the value? Well for starters, the req would effectively have both tags (completed, ready_for_dev). Bubbling this up to the top you'd end up with MF's having nearly all the tags which seems like it'd be useless. I think just choosing one tag and displaying the breakdown/calculation is the way to go.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Apart from it being informational, what else would it affect? It would affect filtering. So filtering by rejected would now include all the non-rejected MFs and a bunch of intermediate (possibly valid) intermediate reqs too. That sounds like shit.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I think it's a clear \\\"no\\\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Don't forget that when a semigroup rule for two values doesn't exist, we simply take both without consolidation. That's orthogonal to this question and decision.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when there's no tag in a child?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when a child has multiple tags?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"We've studied derivative statuses, what about versions?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should we show, where?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"reqtable vs req detail\"}],[{\"lit\":\"subject tag field vs anything else?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"In req detail (at least), it would be cool to display the final tag value, and then next to it, a colour bar indicating the makeup.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Req table is a different kettle of fish because conciseness matters.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Hell we could even use the cell \"},{\"mono\":\"bottom-border\"},{\"lit\":\" to render the bar without padding. That's pretty concise.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":743,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T07:29:39.662177Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":114},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"For \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"status tags\"}]},{\"lit\":\": this will be successful if I can use ShipReq as I have been, but with the following differences:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"when I finish an implementation task, I shouldn't need to update anything else\"}],[{\"lit\":\"when I mark a req as analysed, I shouldn't need to update anything else\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I should always be able to look at an MF's status to comprehend it's collective state (and obviously that data should be correct).\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"For \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"versions\"}]},{\"lit\":\", I basically only want to set them on MFs, and have them automatically propagate to everything else.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"For any derived tag I need to be able to quickly comprehend why the resulting value was derived.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences this could cause?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"It could be confusing if a req has a manually-assigned status tag but you're expecting it to auto-update\"}],[{\"lit\":\"It increases complexity when a users add new tags\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Are there any constraints or rules to which the feature must conform?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Apart from what was outlined in \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":109}},{\"lit\":\" , no.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"There are constraints imposed by ShipReq's core business goals like comprehensibility, and simplicity. But the fact that we'll always explain how derived tags came to be, should address this. Not sure anything else is needed.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Which aspects of the feature are most critical to creating business value?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"automation\"}],[{\"lit\":\"reliability / correctness\"}],[{\"lit\":\"explanation / provenance\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspect of the feature most excites you?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"How much time & effort it will save me from having to manually keep everything up to date\"}],[{\"lit\":\"How much confusion it will save me / how much it will clarify my own mountain of content\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Should we have multiple weighted values instead of a consolidation?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"So instead of (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev = ready_for_dev), what would it be like to just retain (18 completed + 1 ready_for_dev) as the value? Well for starters, the req would effectively have both tags (completed, ready_for_dev). Bubbling this up to the top you'd end up with MF's having nearly all the tags which seems like it'd be useless. I think just choosing one tag and displaying the breakdown/calculation is the way to go.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Apart from it being informational, what else would it affect? It would affect filtering. So filtering by rejected would now include all the non-rejected MFs and a bunch of intermediate (possibly valid) intermediate reqs too. That sounds like shit.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"I think it's a clear \\\"no\\\".\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Don't forget that when a semigroup rule for two values doesn't exist, we simply take both without consolidation. That's orthogonal to this question and decision.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when there's no tag in a child?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should happen when a child has multiple tags?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"We've studied derivative statuses, what about versions?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Will there be any confusion / ambiguity / difficulty in the intersection between derived tags, and default tags?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"It might be an idea to visually mark synthetic tags so that they're distinguishable from manually-assigned tags.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What should we show, where?\"}]},{\"issue\":{\"desc\":[],\"type\":1}},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"reqtable vs req detail\"}],[{\"lit\":\"subject tag field vs anything else?\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"In req detail (at least), it would be cool to display the final tag value, and then next to it, a colour bar indicating the makeup.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Req table is a different kettle of fish because conciseness matters.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"Hell we could even use the cell \"},{\"mono\":\"bottom-border\"},{\"lit\":\" to render the bar without padding. That's pretty concise.\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":744,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-04T07:38:42.621535Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":114},\"value\":[{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"How can we judge the success of the solution?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"For \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"status tags\"}]},{\"lit\":\": this will be successful if I can use ShipReq as I have been, but with the following differences:\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"when I finish an implementation task, I shouldn't need to update anything else\"}],[{\"lit\":\"when I mark a req as analysed, I shouldn't need to update anything else\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I should always be able to look at an MF's status to comprehend it's collective state (and obviously that data should be correct).\"}]]},{\"lit\":\"For \"},{\"**\":[{\"lit\":\"versions\"}]},{\"lit\":\", I basically only want to set them on MFs, and have them automatically propagate to everything else.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"For any derived tag I need to be able to quickly comprehend why the resulting value was derived.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Can you think of any unexpected or adverse consequences this could cause?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"It could be confusing if a req has a manually-assigned status tag but you're expecting it to auto-update\"}],[{\"lit\":\"It increases complexity when a users add new tags\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Are there any constraints or rules to which the feature must conform?\"}]},{\"lit\":\"Apart from what was outlined in \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":109}},{\"lit\":\" , no.\"},{\"bl\":{}},{\"lit\":\"There are constraints imposed by ShipReq's core business goals like comprehensibility, and simplicity. But the fact that we'll always explain how derived tags came to be, should address this. Not sure anything else is needed.\"},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"Which aspects of the feature are most critical to creating business value?\"}]},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"automation\"}],[{\"lit\":\"reliability / correctness\"}],[{\"lit\":\"explanation / provenance\"}]]},{\"h2\":[{\"lit\":\"What aspec