    "{\"#\":858,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-13T01:02:21.340236Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqImplicationsPatch\":{\"dir\":\"<-\",\"id\":{\"gr\":132},\"patch\":{\"+\":[{\"gr\":119}],\"-\":[]}}}}",
    "{\"#\":859,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-13T01:14:57.427498Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":132},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"I just discovered in \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":119}},{\"lit\":\" that when you have a manual tag X in a parent, and a default of Y in a child, the normal derivation rules of X + Y apply. When X + Y = Y, we retain the Y. This is great when X=\"},{\"mono\":\"analysed\"},{\"lit\":\" and Y=\"},{\"mono\":\"ready_for_dev\"},{\"lit\":\" but it's a problem when X=\"},{\"mono\":\"implemented\"},{\"lit\":\". The expectation is that implementing a parent cascades to mark all children as implemented too. It seems we can't have this. So it is a problem or not?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Deepti immediately agreed with the limitation. Having to manually mark each subtask as implemented seems very natural to her. When I explained that I want to automate all of that she suggested having a button in ReqDetail to apply tags to all children.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If we don't have it, I worry that there are still cases where you have to manually chase down reqs to fix there tags - just that it'd be limited to children (instead of children and parents in the world before derivative tags).\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Even with this limitation, the vast majority of the derivative tags problem scenarios are solved. I could just accept that as a win, revisit this in future if it comes up.....\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I guess to fully solve this to my satisfaction, the remaining problem space is: \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"how can one implement additional rules that only affect children and either trump the existing rules, or allow for special cases of default overriding?\"}]}]]}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":860,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-13T01:16:00.035792Z\",\"event\":{\"GenericReqTitleSet\":{\"id\":132,\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"Derivative tags limitation: can't complete a super-task\"}]}}}",
    "{\"#\":861,\"createdAt\":\"2020-08-13T01:16:24.195800Z\",\"event\":{\"ReqFieldCustomTextSet\":{\"fid\":1,\"id\":{\"gr\":132},\"value\":[{\"lit\":\"I just discovered in \"},{\"req\":{\"gr\":119}},{\"lit\":\" that when you have a manual tag X in a parent, and a default of Y in a child, the normal derivation rules of X + Y apply. When X + Y = Y, we retain the Y. This is great when X=\"},{\"mono\":\"analysed\"},{\"lit\":\" and Y=\"},{\"mono\":\"ready_for_dev\"},{\"lit\":\" but it's a problem when X=\"},{\"mono\":\"implemented\"},{\"lit\":\". The expectation is that implementing a parent cascades to mark all children as implemented too. It seems we can't have this. So it is a problem or not?\"},{\"ul\":[[{\"lit\":\"Deepti immediately agreed with the limitation. Having to manually mark each subtask as implemented seems very natural to her. When I explained that I want to automate all of that she suggested having a button in ReqDetail to apply tags to all children.\"}],[{\"lit\":\"If we don't have it, I worry that there are still cases where you have to manually chase down reqs to fix there tags - just that it'd be limited to children (instead of children and parents in the world before derivative tags).\"}],[{\"lit\":\"Even with this limitation, the vast majority of the derivative tags problem scenarios are solved. I could just accept that as a win, revisit this in future if it comes up.....\"}],[{\"lit\":\"I guess to fully solve this to my satisfaction, the remaining problem space is: \"},{\"//\":[{\"lit\":\"how can one implement additional rules that only affect children and either trump the existing rules, or allow for special cases of default overriding?\"}]}]]},{\"lit\":\"I think for now I'll just leave this be and revisit it later.\"}]}}}",
